{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8a655490401e2436", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n2\t\n3\tHaoyu Gu\n4\tghy20050104@gmail.com\n5\tSchool of Future Technology\n6\tSouth China University of Technology\n7\tGuangzhou, China\n8\t\n9\tLekai Qian\n10\t202364870191@mail.scut.edu.cn\n11\tSchool of Future Technology\n12\tSouth China University of Technology\n13\tGuangzhou, China\n14\t\n15\tHaowu Zhou\n16\t202364870491@mail.scut.edu.cn\n17\tSchool of Future Technology\n18\tSouth China University of Technology\n19\tGuangzhou, China\n20\t\n21\tQi Liu∗\n22\tdrliuqi@scut.edu.cn\n23\tSchool of Future Technology\n24\tSouth China University of Technology\n25\tGuangzhou, China\n26\t\n27\tAbstract\n28\t\n29\tMusic creation is fundamentally a process of revision. Yet symbolic\n30\tmusic generation remains dominated by paradigms that produce\n31\tcomplete sequences from scratch, with limited support for selective\n32\tmodification. Edit-based methods have proven effective for text\n33\ttransformation tasks, but remain largely unexplored for symbolic\n34\tmusic. We trace this absence to the representational level: conven-\n35\ttional event-based music encodings lack the structural properties\n36\trequired by explicit music editing. In contrast, the Beat encoding,\n37\ta beat-grid-anchored representation originally designed for au-\n38\ttoregressive generation, possesses structural properties amenable\n39\tto editing. We propose BeatEdit, the first framework for sym-\n40\tbolic music generation based on explicit edit operations, recasting\n41\tgeneration as producing new content by editing a draft rather\n42\tthan synthesizing from scratch. BeatEdit comprises three com-\n43\tplementary mechanisms along an axis of increasing edit density:\n44\tper-token sequence tagging for error correction, iterative refine-\n45\tment for accompaniment editing, and tag-then-fill for segment\n46\tcompletion. All these mechanisms share a single encoding and pre-\n47\ttrained backbone, achieving higher precision and perceptual quality\n48\tthan autoregressive and diffusion methods across all three tasks,\n49\twhile remaining efficient, with single-pass inference completing\n50\tin under 100 ms. Cross-encoding evaluation further reveals that\n51\tencoding design substantially influences editing effectiveness, with\n52\tnotable encoding–method interaction effects. Code is available at\n53\thttps://github.com/Haoyu-Gu/BeatEdit-code.\n54\t\n55\tCCS Concepts\n56\t• Applied computing → Sound and music computing; • Com-\n57\tputing methodologies → Natural language generation.\n58\t\n59\tKeywords\n60\t\n61\tsymbolic music generation, edit-based generation, music represen-\n62\ttation, music tokenization, non-autoregressive generation\n63\t\n64\t∗Corresponding authors.\n65\t\n66\tShuai Wang∗\n67\tshuaiwang@nju.edu.cn\n68\tSchool of Intelligence Science and\n69\tTechnology\n70\tNanjing University\n71\tSuzhou, China\n72\t\n73\t1 Introduction\n74\t\n75\tIn music production, much of the creative effort lies in refining\n76\twhat already exists rather than writing from scratch. A performer\n77\tcorrects wrong notes, an arranger reshapes accompaniment without\n78\taltering the melody, and a composer fills in missing bars while\n79\tpreserving surrounding material. Despite their diversity, these tasks\n80\tshare a common nature: input and output overlap substantially, and\n81\tthe process itself is one of locating what needs change and applying\n82\ttargeted modifications, not regenerating the whole.\n83\t\n84\tSymbolic music generation is currently dominated by two paradigms.\n85\t\n86\tAutoregressive Transformers [13, 18, 27, 33] model music as left-\n87\tto-right event sequences, while diffusion models [14, 23] operate\n88\tover grid-like representations through iterative denoising. Neither\n89\tprovides native support for selective modification: autoregressive\n90\tgeneration must regenerate from the edit point onward even for a\n91\tsingle-note change, and diffusion does not explicitly model which\n92\tpositions require change. Several works attempt local modification\n93\tatop these paradigms, including music inpainting [26], SDEdit-style\n94\tnoise-then-denoise [22], and discrete diffusion conditioning [19].\n95\tHowever, none of these approaches establishes explicit operational\n96\tsemantics for preserving, modifying, or specifying how to modify\n97\tcontent at the symbolic sequence level, and they remain variants\n98\tof implicit generation.\n99\t\n100\tIn natural language processing, edit-based methods have proven\n101\teffective for a variety of text transformation tasks, including gram-\n102\tmatical error correction [2, 24], sentence rewriting [9, 21], and\n103\tcontrolled text generation [20, 30]. These methods share a com-\n104\tmon paradigm: predicting an explicit edit operation (keep, delete,\n105\treplace, or insert) for each input position, which structurally en-\n106\tsures that unedited content is preserved. This paradigm differs from\n107\tmasked infilling and autoregressive completion in mechanism: the\n108\teditor itself localizes the positions to modify and applies typed op-\n109\terations there, whereas conditional generation requires the target\n110\tregion to be specified externally. This naturally raises the question\n111\tof whether overlapping-sequence tasks in symbolic music can be\n112\tsimilarly formulated as explicit editing processes. Music editing\n113\t\n114\tAccepted at the 34th ACM International Conference on Multimedia (MM ’26), Novem-\n115\tber 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. © 2026 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).\n116\tThis is the author’s version of the work. It is posted here for your personal use. Not for\n117\tredistribution. The definitive Version of Record will be published in the Proceedings\n118\tof the 34th ACM International Conference on Multimedia (MM ’26).\n119\t\n120\tarXiv:2607.11124v1  [cs.SD]  13 Jul 2026\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n121\t\n122\tHaoyu Gu et al.\n123\t\n124\tnaturally involves tasks of varying edit density, from correcting\n125\tindividual notes, to reshaping accompaniment parts, to filling in\n126\tmissing passages entirely from context. This spectrum motivates a\n127\tunified editing framework that addresses all three regimes.\n128\t\n129\tAlthough symbolic music and natural language are both se-\n130\tquential and share similar editing needs, edit-based methods well-\n131\testablished in NLP remain largely unexplored for symbolic mu-\n132\tsic. The fundamental obstacle lies at the representational level. In\n133\ttext, words serve as natural atomic units, source and target se-\n134\tquences align position-by-position before and after editing, and\n135\ta single-word modification does not cascade to neighboring po-\n136\tsitions. Existing symbolic music encodings lack these properties:\n137\tin REMI [15], for instance, a single note is scattered across four\n138\tinterleaved tokens, any insertion or deletion shifts all subsequent\n139\tpositions, and the flat event stream provides no structural bound-\n140\tary to contain edit propagation. We formalize this gap as three\n141\tstructural requirements that edit-based methods impose on the\n142\tunderlying encoding (Section 2), and show that the Beat encod-\n143\ting [28], a beat-grid-anchored representation, naturally satisfies\n144\tthem. Its only residual dependency—cascading relative pitch off-\n145\tsets within a beat—is addressed by mechanism-level adaptations\n146\t(Section 3).\n147\t\n148\tTable 1: Edit-compatibility of these existing encodings\n149\t(✓ = satisfied, ✗ = violated, ∼ = partial).\n150\t\n151\tR1 R2 R3 Bottleneck\n152\t\n153\tMIDI-Like [25]\n154\tREMI [15]\n155\tStructured [11]\n156\tCPWord [12]\n157\t\n158\t✗\n159\t✗\n160\t∼\n161\t∼\n162\t\n163\t✓\n164\tBeat [28] (Rel.)\n165\tBeat [28] (Abs.) ✓\n166\t\n167\t✗\n168\t✗\n169\t✗\n170\t✗\n171\t\n172\t✓\n173\t✓\n174\t\n175\t✗\n176\t✗\n177\t∼\n178\t∼\n179\t\n180\t3–4 tok/note; onset/offset decoupled\n181\t4 tok/note; insert/delete shifts all\n182\t4 tok/note; relative time propagates\n183\tFactored heads; no structural grid\n184\t\n185\tRel. pitch cascades within beat\n186\t\n187\t∼\n188\t✓ —\n189\t\n190\tmagnitude faster than autoregressive generation. Ablations fur-\n191\tther show that domain-specific BERT pre-training is the critical\n192\tperformance driver.\n193\t\n194\t2 Edit-Compatible Music Encoding\n195\t2.1 Design Requirements\n196\t\n197\tBuilding on these structural properties, we propose BeatEdit,\n198\ta framework for symbolic music generation based on explicit edit\n199\toperations; throughout, “generation” means producing new con-\n200\ttent by editing a draft, not synthesizing from scratch. BeatEdit\n201\timplements three complementary mechanisms along an axis of in-\n202\tcreasing edit density: per-token sequence tagging for sparse point\n203\tedits, iterative deletion-insertion-prediction for progressive voice-\n204\tlevel refinement, and a two-stage tag-then-fill pipeline for segment\n205\tcompletion. All three mechanisms share the same beat-level en-\n206\tcoding and pre-trained backbone, with dedicated adaptations for\n207\tmusic-specific challenges. Experiments on 192K piano pieces vali-\n208\tdate the framework: edit-based methods achieve higher precision\n209\tand perceptual quality than autoregressive and diffusion baselines\n210\tacross all three tasks, with single-pass inference completing in un-\n211\tder 100 ms, two orders of magnitude faster than autoregressive gen-\n212\teration. Cross-encoding evaluation further reveals that encoding\n213\tdesign substantially influences editing effectiveness, with notable\n214\tencoding–method interaction effects.\n215\t(1) Paradigm. We propose BeatEdit, the first framework that\n216\tformulates symbolic music generation as explicit editing. Three\n217\tcomplementary mechanisms—sequence tagging, iterative re-\n218\tfinement, and tag-then-fill—are designed along an axis of in-\n219\tcreasing edit density, sharing a single pre-trained backbone\n220\twith music-specific adaptations.\n221\t\n222\t(2) Representational analysis. We formalize three structural\n223\trequirements (R1–R3) that edit-based methods impose on the\n224\tunderlying encoding. A 2×2 encoding–method factorial reveals\n225\tthat encoding choice has a statistically significant impact on\n226\tperformance, with strong encoding–method interaction effects,\n227\testablishing it as a previously overlooked design lever.\n228\t\n229\t(3) Empirical results. On 192K piano pieces, edit-based methods\n230\tnearly double the best generative baseline in exact-match cor-\n231\trection with single-pass inference under 100 ms, two orders of\n232\t\n233\tEdit-based methods operate by assigning exactly one edit label\n234\tto each input position. In text, this mechanism works seamlessly\n235\tbecause words naturally serve as atomic units with stable posi-\n236\ttional correspondence. Transferring this paradigm to symbolic mu-\n237\tsic requires the underlying encoding to satisfy three analogous\n238\tproperties:\n239\t\n240\tR1 Atomic edit units. Each note should map to a minimal, self-contained\n241\ttoken group, so that one edit label corresponds to one complete\n242\tediting target.\n243\t\n244\tR2 Trivial source–target alignment. Source and target sequences must\n245\talign position-by-position, so that edit labels can be extracted by\n246\tsimple comparison.\n247\t\n248\tR3 Edit locality. A single-note musical edit should affect only a\n249\tbounded number of tokens in the sequence; the result must re-\n250\tmain a valid encoding without requiring global re-computation.\n251\tAs summarized in Table 1, existing symbolic music encodings\n252\thave difficulty satisfying R1–R3 simultaneously. MIDI-Like [25] and\n253\tREMI [15] both represent each note with 3–4 interleaved tokens,\n254\tscattering onset and duration across non-adjacent positions and\n255\tpreventing self-contained edit units (R1); without a fixed tempo-\n256\tral grid, any insertion or deletion shifts all subsequent positions,\n257\tbreaking positional alignment (R2) and allowing edits to propa-\n258\tgate unboundedly (R3). Structured [11] and CPWord [12] achieve\n259\tpartial atomicity (R1) but lack a structural grid that confines ed-\n260\tits locally: the former relies on relative time-shifts, causing dura-\n261\ttion modifications to propagate to subsequent positions (R2, R3);\n262\tthe latter decomposes attributes into factored prediction heads,\n263\twhose cross-attribute coupling hinders independent per-position\n264\tlabel assignment (R2). Octuple [37] and MMT [6] couple multiple\n265\tdimensions into composite representations or interleaved tracks,\n266\tso that editing a single note involves coordinated changes across\n267\tmulti-dimensional tokens (R1, R3). These failure modes point to a\n268\tcommon structural need: a fixed temporal grid that partitions the\n269\tsequence into content-invariant alignment units, maps each note\n270\tto a compact token group, and bounds edit propagation locally.\n271\t\n272\t\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n273\t\n274\tACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n275\t\n276\tFigure 1: Encoding pipeline. Each pitch becomes a pattern token 𝑠𝑝 (rhythm) and a position token 𝑑 (pitch). Beats from both\n277\tvoices are interleaved with voice markers.\n278\t\n279\t2.2 Beat Encoding\n280\t\n281\tTable 2: Encoding scheme design space (2 × 2).\n282\t\n283\tBeat [28] introduced ternary pattern encoding and relative pitch\n284\tcompression for autoregressive music generation. Its structural\n285\tproperties naturally align with the editing requirements above,\n286\tand we therefore adopt it as the underlying representation for\n287\tBeatEdit. Below we describe the encoding mechanism and show\n288\thow it satisfies R1 and R2; its satisfaction of R3 and the residual\n289\tcascading dependency are discussed in Section 2.3. We adopt a\n290\tdual-voice piano setting (right hand and left hand) with ascending\n291\tpitch order, explicit boundary markers, and no velocity channel.\n292\tThe encoding converts a piano roll into a compact token sequence\n293\tthrough three steps, illustrated in Figure 1: encoding each pitch’s\n294\twithin-beat rhythm as a pattern token, assembling active pitches\n295\tinto a beat-level sequence, and interleaving beats across voices.\n296\tIntuitively, the piano roll is cut into beat-sized columns; within each\n297\tcolumn, every active pitch’s rhythm is compressed into a single\n298\tbase-3 digit string, and the resulting per-beat token groups are laid\n299\tout in temporal order. Token types and ID ranges are detailed in\n300\tAppendix A.\n301\tStep 1: Pattern encoding. We represent each piano piece as a\n302\tthree-state piano roll 𝑋 ∈ {0, 1, 2}𝑃 ×𝑇 , where 𝑃 is the number of\n303\tpitches and 𝑇 the number of time steps, quantized at sixteenth-note\n304\tresolution (𝜏 = 4 steps per beat). Entry 𝑋 [𝑝, 𝑡] is 1 if a note at pitch\n305\t𝑝 has its onset at step 𝑡, 2 if that note is held through step 𝑡, and 0\n306\tif pitch 𝑝 is silent at step 𝑡. Within each beat starting at step 𝑡0, the\n307\tstate vector s𝑝 = (𝑋 [𝑝, 𝑡0], . . . , 𝑋 [𝑝, 𝑡0+𝜏−1]) ∈ {0, 1, 2}𝜏 of pitch 𝑝\n308\tis compressed into a single pattern token via base-3 conversion:\n309\t\n310\t𝑠𝑝 =\n311\t\n312\t𝜏 −1\n313\t∑︁\n314\t\n315\t𝑡 =0\n316\t\n317\ts𝑝 [𝑡] · 3\n318\t\n319\t𝜏 −1−𝑡\n320\t\n321\t(1)\n322\t\n323\tyielding 3𝜏 = 81 possible values. Each pattern token is an atomic\n324\tunit encoding the complete within-beat rhythm of one pitch. For\n325\texample, a quarter note occupies the whole beat as s𝑝 = (1, 2, 2, 2)\n326\tand maps to 𝑠𝑝 = 1·33 + 2·32 + 2·31 + 2·30 = 53; two eighth notes\n327\t(1, 2, 1, 2) map to 𝑠𝑝 = 50.\n328\tStep 2: Beat-level assembly. To eliminate sparsity, only active\n329\tpitches are encoded. For each beat, active pitches are sorted in\n330\tascending order 𝑝 (1) < · · · < 𝑝 (𝑀 ) and encoded using relative\n331\toffsets:\n332\t\n333\t𝑑 ( 𝑗 ) =\n334\t\n335\t(cid:40)𝑝 (1)\n336\t𝑝 ( 𝑗 ) − 𝑝 ( 𝑗 −1)\n337\t\n338\t𝑗 = 1\n339\t𝑗 > 1\n340\t\n341\t(2)\n342\t\n343\tTok/note Vocab Labels Avg. len\n344\t\n345\tA Abs + Sep\n346\tB\n347\tRel + Sep\n348\tC Rel + Bun\n349\tD Abs + Bun\n350\t\n351\t2\n352\t2\n353\t1\n354\t1\n355\t\n356\t186\n357\t185\n358\t7,145\n359\t7,145\n360\t\n361\t350\n362\t350\n363\t14,258\n364\t14,258\n365\t\n366\t1,907\n367\t1,891\n368\t1,163\n369\t1,163\n370\t\n371\tEach note becomes exactly two tokens, a position token 𝑑 ( 𝑗 ) (Eq. 2)\n372\tand a pattern token 𝑠 ( 𝑗 ) := 𝑠𝑝 ( 𝑗 ) , i.e., the pattern token of the 𝑗-th\n373\tactive pitch as defined in Eq. 1, forming a self-contained edit unit\n374\tthat satisfies R1. Empty beats are represented by a single marker\n375\ttoken.\n376\tStep 3: Voice interleaving. Within each bar, beats from both\n377\tvoices are interleaved in a fixed order: melody and accompaniment\n378\talternate at every beat position. Because the temporal axis is par-\n379\ttitioned into fixed-length beats, every beat occupies a dedicated\n380\ttoken span regardless of its content. This ensures that the 𝑛-th beat\n381\tof the source maps to the 𝑛-th beat of the target regardless of local\n382\tedits, providing trivial alignment (R2). Furthermore, each beat is\n383\ta self-contained subsequence delimited by voice markers, so edits\n384\twithin one beat do not affect tokens outside that beat, satisfying\n385\tedit locality (R3). Although we describe dual-voice interleaving\n386\tfor piano, the same mechanism generalizes to multi-track settings\n387\t(Section 4.6). The resulting vocabulary contains 185 tokens; a typ-\n388\tical piano piece encodes to 1,200–2,500 tokens under separated\n389\tencoding.\n390\t\n391\t2.3 Encoding Variants\n392\t\n393\tThe encoding described above follows the original Beat design,\n394\twhich uses relative pitch offsets and separate position and pattern\n395\ttokens. While effective for autoregressive generation, editing intro-\n396\tduces cascading dependencies: under relative encoding, modifying\n397\tone note’s pitch forces the next note’s position token to change as\n398\twell, even though that note is itself correct. This cascade is bounded\n399\twithin a single beat (preserving R3) but motivates exploring alter-\n400\tnative encoding choices. We organize the design space along two\n401\torthogonal axes, yielding a 2 × 2 family of schemes in which the\n402\tbundled variants (C, D) are introduced in this work (Table 2):\n403\t\n404\tPiano Rollp3p2p1t1t2t3t4onsetsustainP pitches × T steps(three-state piano-roll matrix)TernaryencodingTernary PatternState vector: 1212Beat-levelassemblyBeat AssemblySort by pitch ↑Per note:pospat⋮pospatpitch + pattern ID(sorted + position encoding)VoiceinterleavingToken SequenceBART0T1T0T1···BeatTrack 0 (RH)Track 1 (LH)Structure token(voice-interleaved sequence)\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n405\t\n406\tHaoyu Gu et al.\n407\t\n408\tThe first axis is position encoding. The relative scheme (Eq. 2)\n409\texploits music’s translational invariance but introduces cascading\n410\tdependencies, which are handled by the SHIFT mechanism (Sec-\n411\ttion 3.2). The absolute scheme encodes each note’s pitch as a direct\n412\tindex, eliminating cascading at the cost of sacrificing translational\n413\tinvariance. As we show in Section 4, cascading errors compound\n414\tacross refinement rounds, making relative encoding particularly\n415\tproblematic for multi-pass editing methods.\n416\t\n417\tThe second axis is token organization. The separated scheme\n418\trepresents each note as two tokens (position + pattern), keeping\n419\tthe label space compact. The bundled scheme packs both into a\n420\tsingle token, reducing sequence length (Table 2) but expanding the\n421\tvocabulary and label space substantially.\n422\t\n423\tAll four schemes share the same beat-level alignment and can be\n424\tcombined with any editing method. The optimal scheme depends\n425\ton the task–method interaction, as we show in Section 4.\n426\t\n427\t3 The BeatEdit Framework\n428\t\n429\tWith an encoding that satisfies the structural requirements for\n430\tediting in place, we now turn to the mechanisms that operate on it.\n431\tBeatEdit implements three complementary editing mechanisms,\n432\tsequence tagging (§3.2), iterative refinement (§3.3), and tag-then-\n433\tfill (§3.4), all sharing a pre-trained backbone (§3.1). Because all\n434\tmethods operate on the same representation, each can be applied\n435\tacross tasks beyond its primary assignment, a property we exploit\n436\tin Section 4.\n437\t\n438\t3.1 Shared Pre-trained Backbone\n439\t\n440\tThe Beat encoding assigns every beat a self-contained token span,\n441\tallowing a single encoder to serve all three tasks within each en-\n442\tcoding scheme. We use a BERT [4] encoder (8 layers, 512 hidden,\n443\t∼26.6M parameters), pre-trained via masked language modeling on\n444\t192K piano pieces. All three editing methods share this encoder as\n445\ttheir backbone, differing only in the task-specific heads attached\n446\ton top. During pre-training, only music tokens are masked; struc-\n447\ttural tokens (beat boundaries, bar markers) remain visible so that\n448\tthe beat grid required by R2 is preserved throughout. Training is\n449\taugmented with random transposition (±5 semitones). Ablation\n450\texperiments (§4.8) confirm that this pre-training step is the critical\n451\tperformance driver: removing it leads to substantial degradation\n452\tacross all tasks (Appendix L).\n453\t\n454\t3.2 Sequence Tagging\n455\t\n456\tFor sparse point edits, a per-token label can preserve or transform\n457\teach position without length-changing generation. We extend stan-\n458\tdard text edit operations (keep, delete, replace, append) with a\n459\tmusic-specific SHIFT±𝑛 operation that handles the cascading pitch\n460\tdependencies unique to relative encoding (Section 2.3). Given a\n461\tposition token 𝑑𝑖 representing a relative pitch offset, SHIFT applies\n462\tan integer correction:\n463\t\n464\tSHIFT±𝑛 (𝑑𝑖 ) = 𝑑𝑖 ± 𝑛,\n465\t\n466\t𝑛 ∈ {1, . . . , 5}\n467\t\n468\t(3)\n469\t\n470\tThis is necessary because modifying a note’s pitch under relative\n471\tencoding shifts all subsequent offsets within the beat: correcting\n472\tnote 𝑗 from 𝑝 𝑗 to 𝑝 ′\n473\t𝑗 requires simultaneously applying SHIFT𝑝 𝑗 −𝑝′\n474\t𝑗\n475\tto 𝑑 𝑗+1 to maintain the correct absolute pitch of the unchanged note\n476\t\n477\t𝑗+1. Under bundled encoding, each note is a single token and pitch\n478\tcorrections use REPLACE over the full vocabulary instead. The com-\n479\tplete label space comprises 350 labels for separated encoding and\n480\t14,258 for bundled encoding (Appendix B). Edit labels are extracted\n481\tvia beat-level alignment, since perturbations preserve beat count.\n482\tPrediction is decomposed into two heads atop the shared encoder.\n483\tLet h𝑖 ∈ R𝑑 denote the encoder’s hidden representation at position\n484\t𝑖. The binary error detection head predicts whether each token\n485\trequires editing, and the tag prediction head predicts the specific\n486\tedit operation:\n487\t\n488\tˆ𝑒𝑖 = 𝜎 (Wdet h𝑖 + bdet),\n489\t\n490\tˆ𝑡𝑖 = softmax(Wtag h𝑖 + btag)\n491\t\n492\t(4)\n493\t\n494\tAt inference, the detection head gates tag predictions: ˆ𝑡𝑖 is overrid-\n495\tden to KEEP wherever ˆ𝑒𝑖 < 𝜃 , providing a conservative bias against\n496\tunnecessary edits.\n497\t\n498\tTraining pairs are constructed synthetically with fresh random\n499\t\n500\tperturbations each epoch (Appendix G). The combined loss is:\n501\t\n502\tL = Ltag + 𝜆 · Ldetect\n503\t\n504\t(5)\n505\t\n506\twhere Ltag is weighted cross-entropy with down-weighted KEEP to\n507\tcounteract the >85% keep-dominance, and Ldetect is binary cross-\n508\tentropy. Training proceeds with a frozen encoder followed by\n509\tfull fine-tuning with differential learning rates. At inference, the\n510\tmodel iterates up to three rounds with a decode–filter–reencode\n511\tpost-processing cycle to ensure output validity (Algorithm 3 in\n512\tAppendix E; walkthrough in Appendix F).\n513\t\n514\t3.3 Iterative Refinement\n515\t\n516\tWhen edits become denser and span many beats—as in accompani-\n517\tment editing, where tokens must be inserted, deleted, and replaced\n518\tthroughout the accompaniment while preserving the melody—\n519\tsingle-pass tagging cannot adjust sequence length. We address this\n520\tregime with an iterative deletion-insertion-prediction approach.\n521\tThe encoding’s beat-level voice interleaving makes accompaniment\n522\tseparation trivial via positional indexing.\n523\t\n524\tThree task-specific heads are attached to the shared pre-trained\n525\tencoder (§3.1). We adopt two key adaptations for the music domain.\n526\tFirst, an encoder-only architecture provides bidirectional context\n527\tover both melody and partially-refined accompaniment, which we\n528\tfind essential for editing tasks (Section 4.8). Second, per-token ed-\n529\titable flags 𝐸𝑖 ∈ {0, 1} enforce hard melody preservation: all melody\n530\ttokens and structural markers are set to 𝐸𝑖 = 0, and the model is\n531\tconstrained to never modify these positions at both training and\n532\tinference time.\n533\t\n534\tThree heads share the encoder representation h𝑖 : a deletion head\n535\tˆ𝑑𝑖 = 𝜎 (Wdel h𝑖 ) that predicts per-token deletion probability, an\n536\tinsertion head ˆ𝑛 𝑗 = softmax(Wins [h𝑗 ; h𝑗+1]) that predicts the num-\n537\tber of placeholders to insert at gap 𝑗 between adjacent tokens (up to\n538\t20), and a token head ˆ𝑥𝑖 = softmax(Wtok h𝑖 ) that fills all placehold-\n539\ters. The deletion head only operates where 𝐸𝑖 =1; melody tokens\n540\tare never deleted. The joint training loss is:\n541\t\n542\tLiter = Ldel + Lins + Ltok\n543\t\n544\t(6)\n545\t\n546\twhere all three terms are cross-entropy losses. Token prediction\n547\tuses label smoothing (𝜖=0.1) to encourage diversity.\n548\t\n549\t\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n550\t\n551\tACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n552\t\n553\tFigure 2: IterEdit pipeline. Stage 1: BERT MLM pre-training. Stage 2: three heads trained jointly with the encoder. Stage 3:\n554\titerative delete–insert–fill until convergence.\n555\t\n556\tTraining uses a four-level perturbation strategy ranging from\n557\tlight single-note edits (L1) to near-complete accompaniment rewrit-\n558\ting (L4), with intermediate-state sampling: rather than always train-\n559\ting from the fully perturbed input, we sample intermediate states\n560\tby partially applying ground-truth edits, reducing exposure bias\n561\tbetween training and multi-round inference. At inference, each\n562\titeration executes deletion, insertion, and prediction in sequence;\n563\tconvergence is reached when a round produces zero changes (Al-\n564\tgorithm 4 in Appendix H; hyperparameters in Appendix D).\n565\t\n566\t3.4 Tag-then-Fill\n567\t\n568\tany errors are confined to the gap region by construction. Training\n569\tdetails are provided in Appendix D.\n570\t\n571\t4 Experiments\n572\t\n573\tWe evaluate BeatEdit across all three tasks using a unified eval-\n574\tuation framework. We first validate Beat’s structural advantage\n575\tover alternative encodings (§4.2), then present unified main results\n576\t(§4.3), analyze encoding–method interactions (§4.4), report subjec-\n577\ttive listening tests (§4.5), report multi-instrument generalization\n578\t(§4.6), and discuss implications (§4.8).\n579\t\n580\tAt the far end of the edit-density axis, segment completion requires\n581\treconstructing a contiguous span of missing beats from context\n582\talone. Because no source tokens exist within the gap, neither tag-\n583\tging nor iterative refinement can operate; we therefore adopt a\n584\ttwo-stage decomposition into structural allocation (tagging) and\n585\tcontent generation (filling). Both stages use the shared pre-trained\n586\tencoder (§3.1).\n587\tStage 1: Tagging. A tagger assigns each token 𝑥𝑖 one of 11 la-\n588\tbels from the set {KEEP, DELETE, REPLACEM, APPENDM×𝑘 } where\n589\t𝑘 ∈ {1, . . . , 8}, allocating space for missing content. REPLACEM sub-\n590\tstitutes the token with a single [MASK], and APPENDM×𝑘 inserts 𝑘\n591\tmasks after the token. The tagger is trained with Focal Loss [17] to\n592\thandle the strong class imbalance toward KEEP:\n593\t∑︁\n594\t\n595\t(1 − ˆ𝑝𝑖,𝑦𝑖 )𝛾\n596\t\n597\tlog ˆ𝑝𝑖,𝑦𝑖 ,\n598\t\n599\t𝛾 = 2.0\n600\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "a6c26182-3b6c-4097-bc3f-bca74a622107", "uuid": "1964d39d-eec3-4d8a-9cb9-59f7acd42b17", "timestamp": "2026-07-14T08:05:43.457Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/beatedit_full.txt", "content": "BeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n\nHaoyu Gu\nghy20050104@gmail.com\nSchool of Future Technology\nSouth China University of Technology\nGuangzhou, China\n\nLekai Qian\n202364870191@mail.scut.edu.cn\nSchool of Future Technology\nSouth China University of Technology\nGuangzhou, China\n\nHaowu Zhou\n202364870491@mail.scut.edu.cn\nSchool of Future Technology\nSouth China University of Technology\nGuangzhou, China\n\nQi Liu∗\ndrliuqi@scut.edu.cn\nSchool of Future Technology\nSouth China University of Technology\nGuangzhou, China\n\nAbstract\n\nMusic creation is fundamentally a process of revision. Yet symbolic\nmusic generation remains dominated by paradigms that produce\ncomplete sequences from scratch, with limited support for selective\nmodification. Edit-based methods have proven effective for text\ntransformation tasks, but remain largely unexplored for symbolic\nmusic. We trace this absence to the representational level: conven-\ntional event-based music encodings lack the structural properties\nrequired by explicit music editing. In contrast, the Beat encoding,\na beat-grid-anchored representation originally designed for au-\ntoregressive generation, possesses structural properties amenable\nto editing. We propose BeatEdit, the first framework for sym-\nbolic music generation based on explicit edit operations, recasting\ngeneration as producing new content by editing a draft rather\nthan synthesizing from scratch. BeatEdit comprises three com-\nplementary mechanisms along an axis of increasing edit density:\nper-token sequence tagging for error correction, iterative refine-\nment for accompaniment editing, and tag-then-fill for segment\ncompletion. All these mechanisms share a single encoding and pre-\ntrained backbone, achieving higher precision and perceptual quality\nthan autoregressive and diffusion methods across all three tasks,\nwhile remaining efficient, with single-pass inference completing\nin under 100 ms. Cross-encoding evaluation further reveals that\nencoding design substantially influences editing effectiveness, with\nnotable encoding–method interaction effects. Code is available at\nhttps://github.com/Haoyu-Gu/BeatEdit-code.\n\nCCS Concepts\n• Applied computing → Sound and music computing; • Com-\nputing methodologies → Natural language generation.\n\nKeywords\n\nsymbolic music generation, edit-based generation, music represen-\ntation, music tokenization, non-autoregressive generation\n\n∗Corresponding authors.\n\nShuai Wang∗\nshuaiwang@nju.edu.cn\nSchool of Intelligence Science and\nTechnology\nNanjing University\nSuzhou, China\n\n1 Introduction\n\nIn music production, much of the creative effort lies in refining\nwhat already exists rather than writing from scratch. A performer\ncorrects wrong notes, an arranger reshapes accompaniment without\naltering the melody, and a composer fills in missing bars while\npreserving surrounding material. Despite their diversity, these tasks\nshare a common nature: input and output overlap substantially, and\nthe process itself is one of locating what needs change and applying\ntargeted modifications, not regenerating the whole.\n\nSymbolic music generation is currently dominated by two paradigms.\n\nAutoregressive Transformers [13, 18, 27, 33] model music as left-\nto-right event sequences, while diffusion models [14, 23] operate\nover grid-like representations through iterative denoising. Neither\nprovides native support for selective modification: autoregressive\ngeneration must regenerate from the edit point onward even for a\nsingle-note change, and diffusion does not explicitly model which\npositions require change. Several works attempt local modification\natop these paradigms, including music inpainting [26], SDEdit-style\nnoise-then-denoise [22], and discrete diffusion conditioning [19].\nHowever, none of these approaches establishes explicit operational\nsemantics for preserving, modifying, or specifying how to modify\ncontent at the symbolic sequence level, and they remain variants\nof implicit generation.\n\nIn natural language processing, edit-based methods have proven\neffective for a variety of text transformation tasks, including gram-\nmatical error correction [2, 24], sentence rewriting [9, 21], and\ncontrolled text generation [20, 30]. These methods share a com-\nmon paradigm: predicting an explicit edit operation (keep, delete,\nreplace, or insert) for each input position, which structurally en-\nsures that unedited content is preserved. This paradigm differs from\nmasked infilling and autoregressive completion in mechanism: the\neditor itself localizes the positions to modify and applies typed op-\nerations there, whereas conditional generation requires the target\nregion to be specified externally. This naturally raises the question\nof whether overlapping-sequence tasks in symbolic music can be\nsimilarly formulated as explicit editing processes. Music editing\n\nAccepted at the 34th ACM International Conference on Multimedia (MM ’26), Novem-\nber 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. © 2026 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).\nThis is the author’s version of the work. It is posted here for your personal use. Not for\nredistribution. The definitive Version of Record will be published in the Proceedings\nof the 34th ACM International Conference on Multimedia (MM ’26).\n\narXiv:2607.11124v1  [cs.SD]  13 Jul 2026\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nHaoyu Gu et al.\n\nnaturally involves tasks of varying edit density, from correcting\nindividual notes, to reshaping accompaniment parts, to filling in\nmissing passages entirely from context. This spectrum motivates a\nunified editing framework that addresses all three regimes.\n\nAlthough symbolic music and natural language are both se-\nquential and share similar editing needs, edit-based methods well-\nestablished in NLP remain largely unexplored for symbolic mu-\nsic. The fundamental obstacle lies at the representational level. In\ntext, words serve as natural atomic units, source and target se-\nquences align position-by-position before and after editing, and\na single-word modification does not cascade to neighboring po-\nsitions. Existing symbolic music encodings lack these properties:\nin REMI [15], for instance, a single note is scattered across four\ninterleaved tokens, any insertion or deletion shifts all subsequent\npositions, and the flat event stream provides no structural bound-\nary to contain edit propagation. We formalize this gap as three\nstructural requirements that edit-based methods impose on the\nunderlying encoding (Section 2), and show that the Beat encod-\ning [28], a beat-grid-anchored representation, naturally satisfies\nthem. Its only residual dependency—cascading relative pitch off-\nsets within a beat—is addressed by mechanism-level adaptations\n(Section 3).\n\nTable 1: Edit-compatibility of these existing encodings\n(✓ = satisfied, ✗ = violated, ∼ = partial).\n\nR1 R2 R3 Bottleneck\n\nMIDI-Like [25]\nREMI [15]\nStructured [11]\nCPWord [12]\n\n✗\n✗\n∼\n∼\n\n✓\nBeat [28] (Rel.)\nBeat [28] (Abs.) ✓\n\n✗\n✗\n✗\n✗\n\n✓\n✓\n\n✗\n✗\n∼\n∼\n\n3–4 tok/note; onset/offset decoupled\n4 tok/note; insert/delete shifts all\n4 tok/note; relative time propagates\nFactored heads; no structural grid\n\nRel. pitch cascades within beat\n\n∼\n✓ —\n\nmagnitude faster than autoregressive generation. Ablations fur-\nther show that domain-specific BERT pre-training is the critical\nperformance driver.\n\n2 Edit-Compatible Music Encoding\n2.1 Design Requirements\n\nBuilding on these structural properties, we propose BeatEdit,\na framework for symbolic music generation based on explicit edit\noperations; throughout, “generation” means producing new con-\ntent by editing a draft, not synthesizing from scratch. BeatEdit\nimplements three complementary mechanisms along an axis of in-\ncreasing edit density: per-token sequence tagging for sparse point\nedits, iterative deletion-insertion-prediction for progressive voice-\nlevel refinement, and a two-stage tag-then-fill pipeline for segment\ncompletion. All three mechanisms share the same beat-level en-\ncoding and pre-trained backbone, with dedicated adaptations for\nmusic-specific challenges. Experiments on 192K piano pieces vali-\ndate the framework: edit-based methods achieve higher precision\nand perceptual quality than autoregressive and diffusion baselines\nacross all three tasks, with single-pass inference completing in un-\nder 100 ms, two orders of magnitude faster than autoregressive gen-\neration. Cross-encoding evaluation further reveals that encoding\ndesign substantially influences editing effectiveness, with notable\nencoding–method interaction effects.\n(1) Paradigm. We propose BeatEdit, the first framework that\nformulates symbolic music generation as explicit editing. Three\ncomplementary mechanisms—sequence tagging, iterative re-\nfinement, and tag-then-fill—are designed along an axis of in-\ncreasing edit density, sharing a single pre-trained backbone\nwith music-specific adaptations.\n\n(2) Representational analysis. We formalize three structural\nrequirements (R1–R3) that edit-based methods impose on the\nunderlying encoding. A 2×2 encoding–method factorial reveals\nthat encoding choice has a statistically significant impact on\nperformance, with strong encoding–method interaction effects,\nestablishing it as a previously overlooked design lever.\n\n(3) Empirical results. On 192K piano pieces, edit-based methods\nnearly double the best generative baseline in exact-match cor-\nrection with single-pass inference under 100 ms, two orders of\n\nEdit-based methods operate by assigning exactly one edit label\nto each input position. In text, this mechanism works seamlessly\nbecause words naturally serve as atomic units with stable posi-\ntional correspondence. Transferring this paradigm to symbolic mu-\nsic requires the underlying encoding to satisfy three analogous\nproperties:\n\nR1 Atomic edit units. Each note should map to a minimal, self-contained\ntoken group, so that one edit label corresponds to one complete\nediting target.\n\nR2 Trivial source–target alignment. Source and target sequences must\nalign position-by-position, so that edit labels can be extracted by\nsimple comparison.\n\nR3 Edit locality. A single-note musical edit should affect only a\nbounded number of tokens in the sequence; the result must re-\nmain a valid encoding without requiring global re-computation.\nAs summarized in Table 1, existing symbolic music encodings\nhave difficulty satisfying R1–R3 simultaneously. MIDI-Like [25] and\nREMI [15] both represent each note with 3–4 interleaved tokens,\nscattering onset and duration across non-adjacent positions and\npreventing self-contained edit units (R1); without a fixed tempo-\nral grid, any insertion or deletion shifts all subsequent positions,\nbreaking positional alignment (R2) and allowing edits to propa-\ngate unboundedly (R3). Structured [11] and CPWord [12] achieve\npartial atomicity (R1) but lack a structural grid that confines ed-\nits locally: the former relies on relative time-shifts, causing dura-\ntion modifications to propagate to subsequent positions (R2, R3);\nthe latter decomposes attributes into factored prediction heads,\nwhose cross-attribute coupling hinders independent per-position\nlabel assignment (R2). Octuple [37] and MMT [6] couple multiple\ndimensions into composite representations or interleaved tracks,\nso that editing a single note involves coordinated changes across\nmulti-dimensional tokens (R1, R3). These failure modes point to a\ncommon structural need: a fixed temporal grid that partitions the\nsequence into content-invariant alignment units, maps each note\nto a compact token group, and bounds edit propagation locally.\n\n\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n\nACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nFigure 1: Encoding pipeline. Each pitch becomes a pattern token 𝑠𝑝 (rhythm) and a position token 𝑑 (pitch). Beats from both\nvoices are interleaved with voice markers.\n\n2.2 Beat Encoding\n\nTable 2: Encoding scheme design space (2 × 2).\n\nBeat [28] introduced ternary pattern encoding and relative pitch\ncompression for autoregressive music generation. Its structural\nproperties naturally align with the editing requirements above,\nand we therefore adopt it as the underlying representation for\nBeatEdit. Below we describe the encoding mechanism and show\nhow it satisfies R1 and R2; its satisfaction of R3 and the residual\ncascading dependency are discussed in Section 2.3. We adopt a\ndual-voice piano setting (right hand and left hand) with ascending\npitch order, explicit boundary markers, and no velocity channel.\nThe encoding converts a piano roll into a compact token sequence\nthrough three steps, illustrated in Figure 1: encoding each pitch’s\nwithin-beat rhythm as a pattern token, assembling active pitches\ninto a beat-level sequence, and interleaving beats across voices.\nIntuitively, the piano roll is cut into beat-sized columns; within each\ncolumn, every active pitch’s rhythm is compressed into a single\nbase-3 digit string, and the resulting per-beat token groups are laid\nout in temporal order. Token types and ID ranges are detailed in\nAppendix A.\nStep 1: Pattern encoding. We represent each piano piece as a\nthree-state piano roll 𝑋 ∈ {0, 1, 2}𝑃 ×𝑇 , where 𝑃 is the number of\npitches and 𝑇 the number of time steps, quantized at sixteenth-note\nresolution (𝜏 = 4 steps per beat). Entry 𝑋 [𝑝, 𝑡] is 1 if a note at pitch\n𝑝 has its onset at step 𝑡, 2 if that note is held through step 𝑡, and 0\nif pitch 𝑝 is silent at step 𝑡. Within each beat starting at step 𝑡0, the\nstate vector s𝑝 = (𝑋 [𝑝, 𝑡0], . . . , 𝑋 [𝑝, 𝑡0+𝜏−1]) ∈ {0, 1, 2}𝜏 of pitch 𝑝\nis compressed into a single pattern token via base-3 conversion:\n\n𝑠𝑝 =\n\n𝜏 −1\n∑︁\n\n𝑡 =0\n\ns𝑝 [𝑡] · 3\n\n𝜏 −1−𝑡\n\n(1)\n\nyielding 3𝜏 = 81 possible values. Each pattern token is an atomic\nunit encoding the complete within-beat rhythm of one pitch. For\nexample, a quarter note occupies the whole beat as s𝑝 = (1, 2, 2, 2)\nand maps to 𝑠𝑝 = 1·33 + 2·32 + 2·31 + 2·30 = 53; two eighth notes\n(1, 2, 1, 2) map to 𝑠𝑝 = 50.\nStep 2: Beat-level assembly. To eliminate sparsity, only active\npitches are encoded. For each beat, active pitches are sorted in\nascending order 𝑝 (1) < · · · < 𝑝 (𝑀 ) and encoded using relative\noffsets:\n\n𝑑 ( 𝑗 ) =\n\n(cid:40)𝑝 (1)\n𝑝 ( 𝑗 ) − 𝑝 ( 𝑗 −1)\n\n𝑗 = 1\n𝑗 > 1\n\n(2)\n\nTok/note Vocab Labels Avg. len\n\nA Abs + Sep\nB\nRel + Sep\nC Rel + Bun\nD Abs + Bun\n\n2\n2\n1\n1\n\n186\n185\n7,145\n7,145\n\n350\n350\n14,258\n14,258\n\n1,907\n1,891\n1,163\n1,163\n\nEach note becomes exactly two tokens, a position token 𝑑 ( 𝑗 ) (Eq. 2)\nand a pattern token 𝑠 ( 𝑗 ) := 𝑠𝑝 ( 𝑗 ) , i.e., the pattern token of the 𝑗-th\nactive pitch as defined in Eq. 1, forming a self-contained edit unit\nthat satisfies R1. Empty beats are represented by a single marker\ntoken.\nStep 3: Voice interleaving. Within each bar, beats from both\nvoices are interleaved in a fixed order: melody and accompaniment\nalternate at every beat position. Because the temporal axis is par-\ntitioned into fixed-length beats, every beat occupies a dedicated\ntoken span regardless of its content. This ensures that the 𝑛-th beat\nof the source maps to the 𝑛-th beat of the target regardless of local\nedits, providing trivial alignment (R2). Furthermore, each beat is\na self-contained subsequence delimited by voice markers, so edits\nwithin one beat do not affect tokens outside that beat, satisfying\nedit locality (R3). Although we describe dual-voice interleaving\nfor piano, the same mechanism generalizes to multi-track settings\n(Section 4.6). The resulting vocabulary contains 185 tokens; a typ-\nical piano piece encodes to 1,200–2,500 tokens under separated\nencoding.\n\n2.3 Encoding Variants\n\nThe encoding described above follows the original Beat design,\nwhich uses relative pitch offsets and separate position and pattern\ntokens. While effective for autoregressive generation, editing intro-\nduces cascading dependencies: under relative encoding, modifying\none note’s pitch forces the next note’s position token to change as\nwell, even though that note is itself correct. This cascade is bounded\nwithin a single beat (preserving R3) but motivates exploring alter-\nnative encoding choices. We organize the design space along two\northogonal axes, yielding a 2 × 2 family of schemes in which the\nbundled variants (C, D) are introduced in this work (Table 2):\n\nPiano Rollp3p2p1t1t2t3t4onsetsustainP pitches × T steps(three-state piano-roll matrix)TernaryencodingTernary PatternState vector: 1212Beat-levelassemblyBeat AssemblySort by pitch ↑Per note:pospat⋮pospatpitch + pattern ID(sorted + position encoding)VoiceinterleavingToken SequenceBART0T1T0T1···BeatTrack 0 (RH)Track 1 (LH)Structure token(voice-interleaved sequence)\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nHaoyu Gu et al.\n\nThe first axis is position encoding. The relative scheme (Eq. 2)\nexploits music’s translational invariance but introduces cascading\ndependencies, which are handled by the SHIFT mechanism (Sec-\ntion 3.2). The absolute scheme encodes each note’s pitch as a direct\nindex, eliminating cascading at the cost of sacrificing translational\ninvariance. As we show in Section 4, cascading errors compound\nacross refinement rounds, making relative encoding particularly\nproblematic for multi-pass editing methods.\n\nThe second axis is token organization. The separated scheme\nrepresents each note as two tokens (position + pattern), keeping\nthe label space compact. The bundled scheme packs both into a\nsingle token, reducing sequence length (Table 2) but expanding the\nvocabulary and label space substantially.\n\nAll four schemes share the same beat-level alignment and can be\ncombined with any editing method. The optimal scheme depends\non the task–method interaction, as we show in Section 4.\n\n3 The BeatEdit Framework\n\nWith an encoding that satisfies the structural requirements for\nediting in place, we now turn to the mechanisms that operate on it.\nBeatEdit implements three complementary editing mechanisms,\nsequence tagging (§3.2), iterative refinement (§3.3), and tag-then-\nfill (§3.4), all sharing a pre-trained backbone (§3.1). Because all\nmethods operate on the same representation, each can be applied\nacross tasks beyond its primary assignment, a property we exploit\nin Section 4.\n\n3.1 Shared Pre-trained Backbone\n\nThe Beat encoding assigns every beat a self-contained token span,\nallowing a single encoder to serve all three tasks within each en-\ncoding scheme. We use a BERT [4] encoder (8 layers, 512 hidden,\n∼26.6M parameters), pre-trained via masked language modeling on\n192K piano pieces. All three editing methods share this encoder as\ntheir backbone, differing only in the task-specific heads attached\non top. During pre-training, only music tokens are masked; struc-\ntural tokens (beat boundaries, bar markers) remain visible so that\nthe beat grid required by R2 is preserved throughout. Training is\naugmented with random transposition (±5 semitones). Ablation\nexperiments (§4.8) confirm that this pre-training step is the critical\nperformance driver: removing it leads to substantial degradation\nacross all tasks (Appendix L).\n\n3.2 Sequence Tagging\n\nFor sparse point edits, a per-token label can preserve or transform\neach position without length-changing generation. We extend stan-\ndard text edit operations (keep, delete, replace, append) with a\nmusic-specific SHIFT±𝑛 operation that handles the cascading pitch\ndependencies unique to relative encoding (Section 2.3). Given a\nposition token 𝑑𝑖 representing a relative pitch offset, SHIFT applies\nan integer correction:\n\nSHIFT±𝑛 (𝑑𝑖 ) = 𝑑𝑖 ± 𝑛,\n\n𝑛 ∈ {1, . . . , 5}\n\n(3)\n\nThis is necessary because modifying a note’s pitch under relative\nencoding shifts all subsequent offsets within the beat: correcting\nnote 𝑗 from 𝑝 𝑗 to 𝑝 ′\n𝑗 requires simultaneously applying SHIFT𝑝 𝑗 −𝑝′\n𝑗\nto 𝑑 𝑗+1 to maintain the correct absolute pitch of the unchanged note\n\n𝑗+1. Under bundled encoding, each note is a single token and pitch\ncorrections use REPLACE over the full vocabulary instead. The com-\nplete label space comprises 350 labels for separated encoding and\n14,258 for bundled encoding (Appendix B). Edit labels are extracted\nvia beat-level alignment, since perturbations preserve beat count.\nPrediction is decomposed into two heads atop the shared encoder.\nLet h𝑖 ∈ R𝑑 denote the encoder’s hidden representation at position\n𝑖. The binary error detection head predicts whether each token\nrequires editing, and the tag prediction head predicts the specific\nedit operation:\n\nˆ𝑒𝑖 = 𝜎 (Wdet h𝑖 + bdet),\n\nˆ𝑡𝑖 = softmax(Wtag h𝑖 + btag)\n\n(4)\n\nAt inference, the detection head gates tag predictions: ˆ𝑡𝑖 is overrid-\nden to KEEP wherever ˆ𝑒𝑖 < 𝜃 , providing a conservative bias against\nunnecessary edits.\n\nTraining pairs are constructed synthetically with fresh random\n\nperturbations each epoch (Appendix G). The combined loss is:\n\nL = Ltag + 𝜆 · Ldetect\n\n(5)\n\nwhere Ltag is weighted cross-entropy with down-weighted KEEP to\ncounteract the >85% keep-dominance, and Ldetect is binary cross-\nentropy. Training proceeds with a frozen encoder followed by\nfull fine-tuning with differential learning rates. At inference, the\nmodel iterates up to three rounds with a decode–filter–reencode\npost-processing cycle to ensure output validity (Algorithm 3 in\nAppendix E; walkthrough in Appendix F).\n\n3.3 Iterative Refinement\n\nWhen edits become denser and span many beats—as in accompani-\nment editing, where tokens must be inserted, deleted, and replaced\nthroughout the accompaniment while preserving the melody—\nsingle-pass tagging cannot adjust sequence length. We address this\nregime with an iterative deletion-insertion-prediction approach.\nThe encoding’s beat-level voice interleaving makes accompaniment\nseparation trivial via positional indexing.\n\nThree task-specific heads are attached to the shared pre-trained\nencoder (§3.1). We adopt two key adaptations for the music domain.\nFirst, an encoder-only architecture provides bidirectional context\nover both melody and partially-refined accompaniment, which we\nfind essential for editing tasks (Section 4.8). Second, per-token ed-\nitable flags 𝐸𝑖 ∈ {0, 1} enforce hard melody preservation: all melody\ntokens and structural markers are set to 𝐸𝑖 = 0, and the model is\nconstrained to never modify these positions at both training and\ninference time.\n\nThree heads share the encoder representation h𝑖 : a deletion head\nˆ𝑑𝑖 = 𝜎 (Wdel h𝑖 ) that predicts per-token deletion probability, an\ninsertion head ˆ𝑛 𝑗 = softmax(Wins [h𝑗 ; h𝑗+1]) that predicts the num-\nber of placeholders to insert at gap 𝑗 between adjacent tokens (up to\n20), and a token head ˆ𝑥𝑖 = softmax(Wtok h𝑖 ) that fills all placehold-\ners. The deletion head only operates where 𝐸𝑖 =1; melody tokens\nare never deleted. The joint training loss is:\n\nLiter = Ldel + Lins + Ltok\n\n(6)\n\nwhere all three terms are cross-entropy losses. Token prediction\nuses label smoothing (𝜖=0.1) to encourage diversity.\n\n\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n\nACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nFigure 2: IterEdit pipeline. Stage 1: BERT MLM pre-training. Stage 2: three heads trained jointly with the encoder. Stage 3:\niterative delete–insert–fill until convergence.\n\nTraining uses a four-level perturbation strategy ranging from\nlight single-note edits (L1) to near-complete accompaniment rewrit-\ning (L4), with intermediate-state sampling: rather than always train-\ning from the fully perturbed input, we sample intermediate states\nby partially applying ground-truth edits, reducing exposure bias\nbetween training and multi-round inference. At inference, each\niteration executes deletion, insertion, and prediction in sequence;\nconvergence is reached when a round produces zero changes (Al-\ngorithm 4 in Appendix H; hyperparameters in Appendix D).\n\n3.4 Tag-then-Fill\n\nany errors are confined to the gap region by construction. Training\ndetails are provided in Appendix D.\n\n4 Experiments\n\nWe evaluate BeatEdit across all three tasks using a unified eval-\nuation framework. We first validate Beat’s structural advantage\nover alternative encodings (§4.2), then present unified main results\n(§4.3), analyze encoding–method interactions (§4.4), report subjec-\ntive listening tests (§4.5), report multi-instrument generalization\n(§4.6), and discuss implications (§4.8).\n\nAt the far end of the edit-density axis, segment completion requires\nreconstructing a contiguous span of missing beats from context\nalone. Because no source tokens exist within the gap, neither tag-\nging nor iterative refinement can operate; we therefore adopt a\ntwo-stage decomposition into structural allocation (tagging) and\ncontent generation (filling). Both stages use the shared pre-trained\nencoder (§3.1).\nStage 1: Tagging. A tagger assigns each token 𝑥𝑖 one of 11 la-\nbels from the set {KEEP, DELETE, REPLACEM, APPENDM×𝑘 } where\n𝑘 ∈ {1, . . . , 8}, allocating space for missing content. REPLACEM sub-\nstitutes the token with a single [MASK], and APPENDM×𝑘 inserts 𝑘\nmasks after the token. The tagger is trained with Focal Loss [17] to\nhandle the strong class imbalance toward KEEP:\n∑︁\n\n(1 − ˆ𝑝𝑖,𝑦𝑖 )𝛾\n\nlog ˆ𝑝𝑖,𝑦𝑖 ,\n\n𝛾 = 2.0\n", "numLines": 600, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 4133}}}
