{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9457a3da5c8e956c", "type": "tool_result", "content": "600\t\n601\tLtagger = −\n602\t\n603\t(7)\n604\t\n605\t𝑖\n606\t\n607\tThe tagger’s output is deterministically converted into a skeleton\n608\tsequence ˜𝑋 with [MASK] placeholders at positions requiring new\n609\tcontent.\n610\tStage 2: Filling. An inserter predicts tokens at all mask positions.\n611\tRather than filling all masks simultaneously, we adopt an iterative\n612\tconfidence-ranked schedule over 𝑇 =2 passes. At each pass 𝑡, the\n613\tinserter predicts distributions over the vocabulary for all remain-\n614\ting masks; the top ⌊|M|/(𝑇 − 𝑡 + 1)⌋ positions by confidence are\n615\taccepted, and their predictions are committed:\n616\t\n617\tˆ𝑥𝑖 = arg max\n618\t\n619\t𝑣\n620\t\n621\t𝑃ins (𝑣 |\n622\t\n623\t˜𝑋 ),\n624\t\n625\t𝑖 ∈ M𝑡\n626\t\n627\t(8)\n628\t\n629\twhere M𝑡 is the set of unfilled mask positions at pass 𝑡. Only\n630\tmask positions are gathered for prediction, keeping computation\n631\tproportional to the gap size.\n632\t\n633\tThe tagger’s output serves as a hard structural constraint: the\n634\tinserter can only modify positions explicitly marked for filling, so\n635\t\n636\t4.1 Experimental Setup\n637\tDataset. 192,788 piano pieces from the MuseScore Collection, split\n638\t80%/10%/10% train/validation/test at the song level. Sequences ex-\n639\tceeding 2,048 tokens are cropped at bar boundaries. Code, prepro-\n640\tcessing scripts, and configurations are released at https://github.\n641\tcom/Haoyu-Gu/BeatEdit-code.\n642\t\n643\tEncoding schemes. A 2 × 2 factorial design over position encod-\n644\ting—Absolute vs. Relative—and token organization—Separated vs.\n645\tBundled—yields four schemes: A (Abs+Sep), B (Rel+Sep), C (Rel+Bun),\n646\tD (Abs+Bun); see Table 2. For external comparison, we also evaluate\n647\tMIDI-Like [25], Structured [11], REMI [15], and CPWord [12] with\n648\tthe same SeqTag architecture.\n649\t\n650\tMethods. Three editing methods: SeqTag, a sequence tagger for\n651\terror correction (§3.2); IterEdit, an iterative refinement model for\n652\taccompaniment editing (§3.3); and TagFill, a tag-then-fill pipeline\n653\tfor segment completion (§3.4). SeqTag and TagFill share the same\n654\tpre-trained backbone. SeqTag is evaluated on correction and editing.\n655\tIterEdit is trained for editing and correction using the multi-level\n656\tperturbation strategy of §3.3 and evaluated across all four schemes;\n657\ta separate contiguous-masking configuration is used for completion.\n658\tTagFill is evaluated on all three tasks.\n659\t\n660\tBaselines. No-Edit returns the input unchanged; Copy-Ctx\n661\tcopies a random context beat to the corrupted region; BERT-CMLM\n662\tre-predicts all positions via masked language modeling. We include\n663\ttwo families of autoregressive (AR) baselines. AR: for correction\n664\tand editing, a ∼162M-parameter causal LLM (LLaMA) trained from\n665\tscratch on the same data, evaluated under four strategies with in-\n666\tcreasing positional guidance (Prompt, Teacher, Detect, Selective;\n667\tAppendix I.1); the main table reports AR-Detect, which uses Se-\n668\tqTag’s error detector for beat-level localization. For completion,\n669\twe use Anticipatory [32], a ∼128M-parameter AR model with bidi-\n670\trectional infilling, evaluated with its publicly available pre-trained\n671\t\n672\tTokenizedMusicSequenceStage 1: BERT MLM PretrainingoriginalBOST0p40v27T1p55v36EOS15% maskmaskedBOST0[M]v27T1p55[M]EOSBERT Encoder→ p40→ v36predict masked tokensSharingStage 2: IterEdit ModelToken + Position EmbeddingTransformer Encoder × 8Deletion Headkeep / deleteInsertion Head0~20 PLH/gapToken Headpredict vocabrandomly initializedTraining: Levenshtein DP alignmentℒ = ℒdel + ℒins + ℒtok× TStage 3: Iterative InferenceInputBOST0p40v27T1p55v54EOS✗① DelBOST0p40v27T1p55EOSInsert 1 PLH② InsBOST0p40v27T1p55[P]EOS→v36③ FillBOST0p40v27T1p55v36EOSCorrectedMusicSequenceStructural (BOS, EOS, T0, T1)Position (pitch)Value (pattern)[MASK][PLH]Error✗DeletePredictedShared Encoder (from BERT)Token HeadDel/Ins HeadEmbeddingIterate\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n673\t\n674\tHaoyu Gu et al.\n675\t\n676\tTable 3: Cross-encoding comparison.\n677\t\n678\tMIDI-Like†\n679\tStructured\n680\tCPWord\n681\tREMI\n682\t\n683\ttok/note\n684\t\n685\tnf1\n686\t\n687\trecovery\n688\t\n689\t3.75\n690\t4.08\n691\t1.56\n692\t3.59\n693\t\n694\t0.860\n695\t0.882\n696\t0.891\n697\t0.893\n698\t\n699\t−13.1%\n700\t1.3%\n701\t8.4%\n702\t10.0%\n703\t\n704\tMPE↓\n705\t\n706\t—\n707\t0.205\n708\t0.192\n709\t0.183\n710\t\n711\tBeat (Rel, Sep)\n712\tBeat (Rel, Bun)\n713\tBeat (Abs, Bun)\n714\tBeat (Abs, Sep)\n715\t†BERT MLM converged to higher perplexity (PPL = 8.18 vs. ∼1.5 for others).\n716\t\n717\t34.1%\n718\t37.2%\n719\t46.6%\n720\t48.1%\n721\t\n722\t0.923\n723\t0.927\n724\t0.938\n725\t0.940\n726\t\n727\t0.141\n728\t0.135\n729\t0.102\n730\t0.087\n731\t\n732\t2.61\n733\t1.59\n734\t1.59\n735\t2.66\n736\t\n737\tweights. Diffusion uses D3PM [1] discrete diffusion with ∼34M pa-\n738\trameters and SDEdit-style noise-then-denoise at start ratio 𝑟 =0.3;\n739\tAppendix I.2 reports 𝑟 =0.5, 0.7.\n740\t\n741\tEvaluation. 3 tasks × 4 encodings × 200 samples = 2,400 test\n742\tinstances, with 95% bootstrap CIs for key comparisons. Difficulty\n743\tlevels are distributed as L1 : L2 : L3 : L4 = 30 : 30 : 25 : 15. Four metrics\n744\tare reported: beat_exact_match (↑), the fraction of perturbed beats\n745\twith exactly matching tokens; note_f1 (↑), note-level F1; MPE (↓),\n746\tmean pitch error in semitones; and FMD (↓), Fréchet Music Dis-\n747\ttance [31] on full sequences. All metrics except FMD are computed\n748\ton perturbed beats only; full per-scheme breakdowns are reported\n749\tin Appendix K. Note that beat_exact_match and note_f1 reward\n750\tonly recovery of the specific ground truth—appropriate for correc-\n751\ttion, but blind to plausible alternatives; Section 4.7 therefore adds\n752\tdistribution-overlap metrics.\n753\t\n754\t4.2 Cross-Encoding Comparison\n755\t\n756\tAll eight encodings share the same SeqTag architecture, training\n757\tdata, and perturbation protocol, with No-Edit baselines at note_f1\n758\t≈ 0.881–0.884 confirming comparable corruption difficulty. The\n759\tresults separate into three tiers. At the bottom, MIDI-Like [25]\n760\tfalls below the No-Edit baseline, as its flat event stream prevents\n761\teffective MLM pre-training (PPL = 8.18 vs. ∼1.5 for others). Struc-\n762\ttured [11], CPWord [12], and REMI [15] form a middle tier with\n763\tmarginal recovery. All four Beat variants constitute the top tier,\n764\twith the best scheme (Abs Sep) reaching 4.8× higher recovery than\n765\tthe strongest middle-tier encoding and absolute encoding consis-\n766\ttently outperforming relative.\n767\t\n768\tThe comparison with CPWord is particularly instructive: both\n769\tare equally compact (∼1.6 tok/note), yet Beat achieves substantially\n770\thigher recovery. The key difference is structural—Beat’s beat-level\n771\tgrid confines edits locally, whereas CPWord’s factored heads intro-\n772\tduce cross-attribute dependencies. Since all configurations share\n773\tthe identical architecture, the performance gap is entirely attribut-\n774\table to encoding design.\n775\t\n776\t4.3 Main Results\n777\t\n778\tTable 4 summarizes the best configuration per method–task combi-\n779\tnation across all encoding schemes.\n780\t\n781\tFor error correction, SeqTag and IterEdit achieve near-identical\n782\tbeat exact match (0.726 vs. 0.719), both nearly doubling the best\n783\tgenerative baselines (≤0.394). The advantage is consistent across all\n784\t\n785\tmetrics (Table 4). TagFill trails at 0.368, indicating that its two-stage\n786\tdecomposition introduces cascade errors on a task where most edits\n787\tare single-token replacements.\n788\t\n789\tFor accompaniment editing, IterEdit leads at 0.480, surpassing\n790\tSeqTag (0.408) and TagFill (0.350), with the lowest FMD among\n791\tediting methods. The per-difficulty breakdown (Table 5b) reveals\n792\ta crossover: SeqTag dominates at L1 where most edits are single-\n793\ttoken replacements amenable to one-pass tagging, while IterEdit’s\n794\titerativeloop overtakes at L2–L4 as multi-token insertions and dele-\n795\ttions become frequent. At L4 (near-complete rewriting), all methods\n796\tdrop sharply to below 0.10, approaching the structural boundary\n797\twhere editing yields to generation.\n798\t\n799\tSegment completion pushes edit density to its extreme: the\n800\tentire gap contains no source tokens. SeqTag is inapplicable here as\n801\tit has no generation head. TagFill dominates (beat: 0.436), reflecting\n802\tthe natural alignment between its masked-token inserter and the\n803\tcontiguous-gap structure. IterEdit achieves only 0.120, confirming\n804\tthat iterative refinement is less suited to generation from empty\n805\tspans. Among baselines, Anticipatory [32]—an AR model designed\n806\tfor music infilling—achieves low token-level precision (beat: 0.069),\n807\tillustrating the gap between generating plausible music and recov-\n808\tering specific target content. All other baselines also fall well below\n809\tTagFill.\n810\t\n811\tAcross all three tasks, editing methods outperform generative\n812\tbaselines. The AR-Detect variant—which pairs SeqTag’s error de-\n813\ttector with autoregressive regeneration—trails editing methods by\n814\tlarge margins despite using identical beat-level localization, con-\n815\tfirming that the advantage lies in the edit mechanism itself rather\n816\tthan in error localization alone.\n817\t\n818\t4.4 Encoding × Method Analysis\n819\tThe 2 × 2 encoding analysis reveals that encoding choice interacts\n820\tstrongly with method design, and in several cases rivaling method\n821\tchoice as a performance lever.\n822\t\n823\tRelative vs. absolute position. For TagFill and IterEdit, absolute\n824\tencoding is superior in most matched pairs (Table 5a). Notably, this\n825\treverses the relative-over-absolute preference reported for autore-\n826\tgressive generation in the original Beat work [28]: the ranking\n827\tthat holds under generation does not carry over to editing. The\n828\tcause is cascading dependencies: under relative encoding, modifying\n829\tone pitch shifts all subsequent offsets within the beat, a bounded\n830\tbut compounding error that multi-pass methods amplify across\n831\trefinement rounds. SeqTag, by contrast, applies all edits in a single\n832\tpass and is immune to cascading—Scheme B (Rel+Sep) achieves\n833\tits highest correction score, benefiting from relative encoding’s\n834\ttranslational invariance as a classification feature.\n835\t\n836\tSeparated vs. bundled tokens. TagFill generally favors separated\n837\tencoding (correction and completion), as its MLM-based inserter\n838\tbenefits from the richer per-token signal of two-token notes; editing\n839\tis the exception, where bundled Scheme D slightly leads. IterEdit’s\n840\tpreference is task-dependent: separated for correction, bundled for\n841\tediting, where shorter sequences reduce iterative passes. SeqTag is\n842\tlargely insensitive to this axis.\n843\t\n844\tThese two axes interact most dramatically at Scheme B (Rel+Sep),\n845\twhere TagFill and IterEdit collapse below 0.10 while SeqTag achieves\n846\tits highest score. The encoding×method interaction is statistically\n847\t\n848\t\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n849\t\n850\tACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n851\t\n852\tTable 4: Main results (best scheme per method, perturbed beats only).\n853\t\n854\tError Correction\n855\t\n856\tAccomp. Editing\n857\t\n858\tSegment Completion\n859\t\n860\tMethod\n861\t\n862\tSeqTag\n863\tIterEdit\n864\tTagFill\n865\t\n866\tbeat↑\n867\t.726B\n868\t.719A\n869\t.368A\n870\t\n871\t.030\n872\tNo-Edit\n873\tCopy-Ctx\n874\t.12