ing (4.07).\n1142\t\n1143\t4.6 Multi-Instrument Generalization\n1144\t\n1145\tWe construct a multi-track dataset from the Lakh MIDI Dataset [29]\n1146\t(108K pieces, 105 General MIDI programs, 2–10 tracks per piece).\n1147\tEach piece is encoded using the Beat encoding’s standard multi-\n1148\ttrack interleaving mechanism, where beats from all voices are in-\n1149\tterleaved at the beat level, and evaluated under Scheme C. Table 7\n1150\tshows the framework transfers across all three tasks.\n1151\t\n1152\tTask\n1153\t\n1154\tSystem\n1155\t\n1156\tAvg MOS\n1157\t\n1158\tCorr. (Enc.)\n1159\t\n1160\tCorr. (Method)\n1161\t\n1162\tBeat-C + SeqTag\n1163\tREMI + SeqTag\n1164\tCPWord + SeqTag\n1165\tStructured + SeqTag\n1166\t\n1167\tSeqTag\n1168\tIterEdit\n1169\tDiffusion / CMLM\n1170\tAR-Detect\n1171\t\n1172\tCompl.\n1173\t\n1174\tEdit.\n1175\t\n1176\tTagFill\n1177\tIterEdit\n1178\tAnticipatory\n1179\t\n1180\tIterEdit\n1181\tSeqTag\n1182\tTagFill\n1183\tDiffusion\n1184\t\n1185\t4.24\n1186\t2.80\n1187\t2.69\n1188\t2.45\n1189\t4.21\n1190\t4.13\n1191\t3.25\n1192\t3.05\n1193\t4.15\n1194\t3.42\n1195\t2.86\n1196\t4.07\n1197\t3.91\n1198\t3.83\n1199\t2.94\n1200\t\n1201\tDue to distributional differences between multi-track ensemble\n1202\tdata and the dual-voice piano data used for training, evaluation\n1203\t\n1204\t\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n1205\t\n1206\tHaoyu Gu et al.\n1207\t\n1208\tTable 7: Multi-track generalization (Scheme C, perturbed\n1209\tbeats only).\n1210\t\n1211\tTask\n1212\t\n1213\tSetting\n1214\t\n1215\tbeat↑ nf1↑\n1216\t\n1217\tcf1↑\n1218\t\n1219\tCorr.\n1220\t\n1221\tEdit.\n1222\t\n1223\tCompl.\n1224\t\n1225\tPiano\n1226\tMulti\n1227\t\n1228\tPiano\n1229\tMulti\n1230\t\n1231\tPiano\n1232\tMulti\n1233\t\n1234\t.400\n1235\t.258\n1236\t\n1237\t.269\n1238\t.196\n1239\t\n1240\t.298\n1241\t.271\n1242\t\n1243\t.531\n1244\t.797\n1245\t\n1246\t.435\n1247\t.534\n1248\t\n1249\t.442\n1250\t.494\n1251\t\n1252\t.546\n1253\t.804\n1254\t\n1255\t.448\n1256\t.568\n1257\t\n1258\t.507\n1259\t.628\n1260\t\n1261\tTable 8: Segment completion on POP909 (204 segments).\n1262\tPoly.+chord additionally receives ground-truth chords.\n1263\t\n1264\tMethod\n1265\t\n1266\tbme↑ nf1↑ 𝐷𝑃 ↑ 𝐷𝐷 ↑ IOI↑ CTA↑ ms↓\n1267\t\n1268\tTagFill-A\n1269\tTagFill-D\n1270\tPolyffusion\n1271\t\n1272\t.083\n1273\t.087\n1274\t.009\n1275\t\n1276\t.907\n1277\t.254\n1278\t.279 .913\n1279\t.856\n1280\t.060\n1281\t\n1282\t.860\n1283\t.924\n1284\t.914\n1285\t\n1286\t.680\n1287\t.805\n1288\t.867\n1289\t\n1290\t.604\n1291\t.576\n1292\t.427\n1293\t\n1294\t35\n1295\t35\n1296\t1747\n1297\t\n1298\tPoly.+chord\n1299\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "a6c26182-3b6c-4097-bc3f-bca74a622107", "uuid": "0c40a913-9fcb-4436-bf31-7171ab21cfab", "timestamp": "2026-07-14T08:05:59.138Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/beatedit_full.txt", "content": "\nLtagger = −\n\n(7)\n\n𝑖\n\nThe tagger’s output is deterministically converted into a skeleton\nsequence ˜𝑋 with [MASK] placeholders at positions requiring new\ncontent.\nStage 2: Filling. An inserter predicts tokens at all mask positions.\nRather than filling all masks simultaneously, we adopt an iterative\nconfidence-ranked schedule over 𝑇 =2 passes. At each pass 𝑡, the\ninserter predicts distributions over the vocabulary for all remain-\ning masks; the top ⌊|M|/(𝑇 − 𝑡 + 1)⌋ positions by confidence are\naccepted, and their predictions are committed:\n\nˆ𝑥𝑖 = arg max\n\n𝑣\n\n𝑃ins (𝑣 |\n\n˜𝑋 ),\n\n𝑖 ∈ M𝑡\n\n(8)\n\nwhere M𝑡 is the set of unfilled mask positions at pass 𝑡. Only\nmask positions are gathered for prediction, keeping computation\nproportional to the gap size.\n\nThe tagger’s output serves as a hard structural constraint: the\ninserter can only modify positions explicitly marked for filling, so\n\n4.1 Experimental Setup\nDataset. 192,788 piano pieces from the MuseScore Collection, split\n80%/10%/10% train/validation/test at the song level. Sequences ex-\nceeding 2,048 tokens are cropped at bar boundaries. Code, prepro-\ncessing scripts, and configurations are released at https://github.\ncom/Haoyu-Gu/BeatEdit-code.\n\nEncoding schemes. A 2 × 2 factorial design over position encod-\ning—Absolute vs. Relative—and token organization—Separated vs.\nBundled—yields four schemes: A (Abs+Sep), B (Rel+Sep), C (Rel+Bun),\nD (Abs+Bun); see Table 2. For external comparison, we also evaluate\nMIDI-Like [25], Structured [11], REMI [15], and CPWord [12] with\nthe same SeqTag architecture.\n\nMethods. Three editing methods: SeqTag, a sequence tagger for\nerror correction (§3.2); IterEdit, an iterative refinement model for\naccompaniment editing (§3.3); and TagFill, a tag-then-fill pipeline\nfor segment completion (§3.4). SeqTag and TagFill share the same\npre-trained backbone. SeqTag is evaluated on correction and editing.\nIterEdit is trained for editing and correction using the multi-level\nperturbation strategy of §3.3 and evaluated across all four schemes;\na separate contiguous-masking configuration is used for completion.\nTagFill is evaluated on all three tasks.\n\nBaselines. No-Edit returns the input unchanged; Copy-Ctx\ncopies a random context beat to the corrupted region; BERT-CMLM\nre-predicts all positions via masked language modeling. We include\ntwo families of autoregressive (AR) baselines. AR: for correction\nand editing, a ∼162M-parameter causal LLM (LLaMA) trained from\nscratch on the same data, evaluated under four strategies with in-\ncreasing positional guidance (Prompt, Teacher, Detect, Selective;\nAppendix I.1); the main table reports AR-Detect, which uses Se-\nqTag’s error detector for beat-level localization. For completion,\nwe use Anticipatory [32], a ∼128M-parameter AR model with bidi-\nrectional infilling, evaluated with its publicly available pre-trained\n\nTokenizedMusicSequenceStage 1: BERT MLM PretrainingoriginalBOST0p40v27T1p55v36EOS15% maskmaskedBOST0[M]v27T1p55[M]EOSBERT Encoder→ p40→ v36predict masked tokensSharingStage 2: IterEdit ModelToken + Position EmbeddingTransformer Encoder × 8Deletion Headkeep / deleteInsertion Head0~20 PLH/gapToken Headpredict vocabrandomly initializedTraining: Levenshtein DP alignmentℒ = ℒdel + ℒins + ℒtok× TStage 3: Iterative InferenceInputBOST0p40v27T1p55v54EOS✗① DelBOST0p40v27T1p55EOSInsert 1 PLH② InsBOST0p40v27T1p55[P]EOS→v36③ FillBOST0p40v27T1p55v36EOSCorrectedMusicSequenceStructural (BOS, EOS, T0, T1)Position (pitch)Value (pattern)[MASK][PLH]Error✗DeletePredictedShared Encoder (from BERT)Token HeadDel/Ins HeadEmbeddingIterate\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nHaoyu Gu et al.\n\nTable 3: Cross-encoding comparison.\n\nMIDI-Like†\nStructured\nCPWord\nREMI\n\ntok/note\n\nnf1\n\nrecovery\n\n3.75\n4.08\n1.56\n3.59\n\n0.860\n0.882\n0.891\n0.893\n\n−13.1%\n1.3%\n8.4%\n10.0%\n\nMPE↓\n\n—\n0.205\n0.192\n0.183\n\nBeat (Rel, Sep)\nBeat (Rel, Bun)\nBeat (Abs, Bun)\nBeat (Abs, Sep)\n†BERT MLM converged to higher perplexity (PPL = 8.18 vs. ∼1.5 for others).\n\n34.1%\n37.2%\n46.6%\n48.1%\n\n0.923\n0.927\n0.938\n0.940\n\n0.141\n0.135\n0.102\n0.087\n\n2.61\n1.59\n1.59\n2.66\n\nweights. Diffusion uses D3PM [1] discrete diffusion with ∼34M pa-\nrameters and SDEdit-style noise-then-denoise at start ratio 𝑟 =0.3;\nAppendix I.2 reports 𝑟 =0.5, 0.7.\n\nEvaluation. 3 tasks × 4 encodings × 200 samples = 2,400 test\ninstances, with 95% bootstrap CIs for key comparisons. Difficulty\nlevels are distributed as L1 : L2 : L3 : L4 = 30 : 30 : 25 : 15. Four metrics\nare reported: beat_exact_match (↑), the fraction of perturbed beats\nwith exactly matching tokens; note_f1 (↑), note-level F1; MPE (↓),\nmean pitch error in semitones; and FMD (↓), Fréchet Music Dis-\ntance [31] on full sequences. All metrics except FMD are computed\non perturbed beats only; full per-scheme breakdowns are reported\nin Appendix K. Note that beat_exact_match and note_f1 reward\nonly recovery of the specific ground truth—appropriate for correc-\ntion, but blind to plausible alternatives; Section 4.7 therefore adds\ndistribution-overlap metrics.\n\n4.2 Cross-Encoding Comparison\n\nAll eight encodings share the same SeqTag architecture, training\ndata, and perturbation protocol, with No-Edit baselines at note_f1\n≈ 0.881–0.884 confirming comparable corruption difficulty. The\nresults separate into three tiers. At the bottom, MIDI-Like [25]\nfalls below the No-Edit baseline, as its flat event stream prevents\neffective MLM pre-training (PPL = 8.18 vs. ∼1.5 for others). Struc-\ntured [11], CPWord [12], and REMI [15] form a middle tier with\nmarginal recovery. All four Beat variants constitute the top tier,\nwith the best scheme (Abs Sep) reaching 4.8× higher recovery than\nthe strongest middle-tier encoding and absolute encoding consis-\ntently outperforming relative.\n\nThe comparison with CPWord is particularly instructive: both\nare equally compact (∼1.6 tok/note), yet Beat achieves substantially\nhigher recovery. The key difference is structural—Beat’s beat-level\ngrid confines edits locally, whereas CPWord’s factored heads intro-\nduce cross-attribute dependencies. Since all configurations share\nthe identical architecture, the performance gap is entirely attribut-\nable to encoding design.\n\n4.3 Main Results\n\nTable 4 summarizes the best configuration per method–task combi-\nnation across all encoding schemes.\n\nFor error correction, SeqTag and IterEdit achieve near-identical\nbeat exact match (0.726 vs. 0.719), both nearly doubling the best\ngenerative baselines (≤0.394). The advantage is consistent across all\n\nmetrics (Table 4). TagFill trails at 0.368, indicating that its two-stage\ndecomposition introduces cascade errors on a task where most edits\nare single-token replacements.\n\nFor accompaniment editing, IterEdit leads at 0.480, surpassing\nSeqTag (0.408) and TagFill (0.350), with the lowest FMD among\nediting methods. The per-difficulty breakdown (Table 5b) reveals\na crossover: SeqTag dominates at L1 where most edits are single-\ntoken replacements amenable to one-pass tagging, while IterEdit’s\niterativeloop overtakes at L2–L4 as multi-token insertions and dele-\ntions become frequent. At L4 (near-complete rewriting), all methods\ndrop sharply to below 0.10, approaching the structural boundary\nwhere editing yields to generation.\n\nSegment completion pushes edit density to its extreme: the\nentire gap contains no source tokens. SeqTag is inapplicable here as\nit has no generation head. TagFill dominates (beat: 0.436), reflecting\nthe natural alignment between its masked-token inserter and the\ncontiguous-gap structure. IterEdit achieves only 0.120, confirming\nthat iterative refinement is less suited to generation from empty\nspans. Among baselines, Anticipatory [32]—an AR model designed\nfor music infilling—achieves low token-level precision (beat: 0.069),\nillustrating the gap between generating plausible music and recov-\nering specific target content. All other baselines also fall well below\nTagFill.\n\nAcross all three tasks, editing methods outperform generative\nbaselines. The AR-Detect variant—which pairs SeqTag’s error de-\ntector with autoregressive regeneration—trails editing methods by\nlarge margins despite using identical beat-level localization, con-\nfirming that the advantage lies in the edit mechanism itself rather\nthan in error localization alone.\n\n4.4 Encoding × Method Analysis\nThe 2 × 2 encoding analysis reveals that encoding choice interacts\nstrongly with method design, and in several cases rivaling method\nchoice as a performance lever.\n\nRelative vs. absolute position. For TagFill and IterEdit, absolute\nencoding is superior in most matched pairs (Table 5a). Notably, this\nreverses the relative-over-absolute preference reported for autore-\ngressive generation in the original Beat work [28]: the ranking\nthat holds under generation does not carry over to editing. The\ncause is cascading dependencies: under relative encoding, modifying\none pitch shifts all subsequent offsets within the beat, a bounded\nbut compounding error that multi-pass methods amplify across\nrefinement rounds. SeqTag, by contrast, applies all edits in a single\npass and is immune to cascading—Scheme B (Rel+Sep) achieves\nits highest correction score, benefiting from relative encoding’s\ntranslational invariance as a classification feature.\n\nSeparated vs. bundled tokens. TagFill generally favors separated\nencoding (correction and completion), as its MLM-based inserter\nbenefits from the richer per-token signal of two-token notes; editing\nis the exception, where bundled Scheme D slightly leads. IterEdit’s\npreference is task-dependent: separated for correction, bundled for\nediting, where shorter sequences reduce iterative passes. SeqTag is\nlargely insensitive to this axis.\n\nThese two axes interact most dramatically at Scheme B (Rel+Sep),\nwhere TagFill and IterEdit collapse below 0.10 while SeqTag achieves\nits highest score. The encoding×method interaction is statistically\n\n\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n\nACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nTable 4: Main results (best scheme per method, perturbed beats only).\n\nError Correction\n\nAccomp. Editing\n\nSegment Completion\n\nMethod\n\nSeqTag\nIterEdit\nTagFill\n\nbeat↑\n.726B\n.719A\n.368A\n\n.030\nNo-Edit\nCopy-Ctx\n.129\nBERT-CMLM .388D\n.390D\nDiffusion\nAR†\n.394A\n\nnf1↑\n.855\n.849\n.667\n\n.644\n.429\n.659\n.602\n.650\n\nFMD↓\n0.15\n1.03\n2.03\n\n2.69\n7.74\n1.01\n0.87\n1.24\n\nbeat↑\n.408C\n.480D\n.350D\n\n.037\n.127\n.188D\n.200C\n.278A\n\nnf1↑\n\nFMD↓\n\nbeat↑\n\nnf1↑\n\nFMD↓\n\n.574\n.607\n.519\n\n.473\n.368\n.456\n.372\n.478\n\n2.56\n1.19\n1.24\n\n2.48\n3.80\n0.97\n2.75\n1.73\n\n.120A\n.436A\n\n.000\n.116\n.111A\n.080D\n.069\n\nN/A\n.212\n.557\n\n.000\n.032\n.042\n.228\n.027\n\n0.34\n0.27\n\n1.76\n2.62\n2.22\n>10\n5.69\n\n†Correction & editing: AR-Detect (LLaMA 162M + SeqTag error detector; Appendix I.1). Completion: Anticipatory [32] (128M, pre-trained, bidirectional infilling).\n\nTable 5: Beat exact match: (a) by encoding scheme, (b) by difficulty level.\n\n(a) Encoding × Method\n\n(b) Difficulty Level\n\nTask\n\nMethod\n\nA\n\nB\n\nC\n\nD\n\nTask\n\nMethod\n\nL1\n\nL2\n\nL3\n\nL4\n\nCorr.\n\nEdit.\n\nCompl.\n\nSeqTag\nIterEdit\nTagFill\n\nSeqTag\nIterEdit\nTagFill\n\nIterEdit\nTagFill\n\n.700\n.719\n.368\n\n.382\n.458\n.321\n.120\n.436\n\n.726\n.070\n.061\n\n.394\n.069\n.089\n\n.060\n.264\n\n.702\n.412\n.335\n.408\n.352\n.301\n\n.011\n.298\n\n.700\n.569\n.329\n\n.399\n.480\n.350\n\n.005\n.326\n\nCorr.\n\nEdit.\n\nCompl.\n\nSeqTagB\nIterEditA\nTagFillA\nSeqTagC\nIterEditD\nTagFillD\nIterEditA\nTagFillD\n\n.757\n.790\n.407\n.773\n.763\n.477\n\n.168\n.416\n\n.737\n.743\n.421\n\n.415\n.583\n.442\n\n.112\n.362\n\n.700\n.647\n.256\n\n.208\n.298\n.286\n\n.108\n.353\n\n.690\n.664\n.379\n\n.045\n.090\n.076\n\n.092\n.313\n\nsignificant (Appendix M), confirming that encoding choice is a\nsignificant design lever alongside method architecture.\n\nTable 6: Subjective MOS (average of MQ, NA, EA; 1–5 scale).\nPer-dimension breakdown in Appendix N.\n\n4.5 Subjective Evaluation\n\nWe recruited 33 evaluators to rate outputs on a 1–5 MOS scale\nacross music quality, naturalness, and edit accuracy (details in Ap-\npendix N).\n\nResults are consistent with objective metrics across all four exper-\niments. For encoding comparison, Beat provides a 1.4–1.8 MOS ad-\nvantage over REMI, CPWord, and Structured under the same SeqTag\narchitecture, with the largest gap in naturalness. For method com-\nparison, edit-based methods consistently outperform generative\nbaselines: on correction, SeqTag (4.21) and IterEdit (4.13) score well\nabove Diffusion/CMLM (3.25) and AR-Detect (3.05). Task-specific\nspecialization is confirmed: SeqTag leads correction, TagFill leads\ncompletion (4.15), and IterEdit leads editing (4.07).\n\n4.6 Multi-Instrument Generalization\n\nWe construct a multi-track dataset from the Lakh MIDI Dataset [29]\n(108K pieces, 105 General MIDI programs, 2–10 tracks per piece).\nEach piece is encoded using the Beat encoding’s standard multi-\ntrack interleaving mechanism, where beats from all voices are in-\nterleaved at the beat level, and evaluated under Scheme C. Table 7\nshows the framework transfers across all three tasks.\n\nTask\n\nSystem\n\nAvg MOS\n\nCorr. (Enc.)\n\nCorr. (Method)\n\nBeat-C + SeqTag\nREMI + SeqTag\nCPWord + SeqTag\nStructured + SeqTag\n\nSeqTag\nIterEdit\nDiffusion / CMLM\nAR-Detect\n\nCompl.\n\nEdit.\n\nTagFill\nIterEdit\nAnticipatory\n\nIterEdit\nSeqTag\nTagFill\nDiffusion\n\n4.24\n2.80\n2.69\n2.45\n4.21\n4.13\n3.25\n3.05\n4.15\n3.42\n2.86\n4.07\n3.91\n3.83\n2.94\n\nDue to distributional differences between multi-track ensemble\ndata and the dual-voice piano data used for training, evaluation\n\n\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nHaoyu Gu et al.\n\nTable 7: Multi-track generalization (Scheme C, perturbed\nbeats only).\n\nTask\n\nSetting\n\nbeat↑ nf1↑\n\ncf1↑\n\nCorr.\n\nEdit.\n\nCompl.\n\nPiano\nMulti\n\nPiano\nMulti\n\nPiano\nMulti\n\n.400\n.258\n\n.269\n.196\n\n.298\n.271\n\n.531\n.797\n\n.435\n.534\n\n.442\n.494\n\n.546\n.804\n\n.448\n.568\n\n.507\n.628\n\nTable 8: Segment completion on POP909 (204 segments).\nPoly.+chord additionally receives ground-truth chords.\n\nMethod\n\nbme↑ nf1↑ 𝐷𝑃 ↑ 𝐷𝐷 ↑ IOI↑ CTA↑ ms↓\n\nTagFill-A\nTagFill-D\nPolyffusion\n\n.083\n.087\n.009\n\n.907\n.254\n.279 .913\n.856\n.060\n\n.860\n.924\n.914\n\n.680\n.805\n.867\n\n.604\n.576\n.427\n\n35\n35\n1747\n\nPoly.+chord\n", "numLines": 700, "startLine": 600, "totalLines": 4