{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8aa56f74718bd6d1", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1300\t.013\n1301\t\n1302\t.084\n1303\t\n1304\t.889\n1305\t\n1306\t.930\n1307\t\n1308\t.945\n1309\t\n1310\t.725\n1311\t\n1312\t1747\n1313\t\n1314\tmetrics exhibit systematic shifts: beat exact match is lower, reflect-\n1315\ting the denser merged voices and greater harmonic complexity of\n1316\tensemble arrangements, while note-level metrics are higher (nf1\n1317\t.531→.797 on correction), indicating that musical content is still\n1318\tcaptured under the shift. These results preliminarily show that\n1319\tthe framework transfers to multi-instrument settings without ar-\n1320\tchitectural modification; a comprehensive evaluation across many\n1321\theterogeneous tracks and instrument roles remains future work.\n1322\tDetails are provided in Appendix P.\n1323\t\n1324\t4.7 External Comparison and the\n1325\tEditing–Generation Boundary\n1326\t\n1327\tComparison with Polyffusion. We compare TagFill against the\n1328\tdiffusion model Polyffusion [23] on segment completion over its\n1329\thome dataset POP909 (4/4 pieces; song-level split: 161 train / 20\n1330\ttest songs, 204 eight-bar segments): given the melody and flanking\n1331\taccompaniment, fill four interior bars. The setup is conservative for\n1332\tus—Polyffusion’s official checkpoint was trained on all of POP909\n1333\tincluding our test songs, whereas TagFill fine-tunes its inserter\n1334\tonly on the training split—and both receive equal information (no\n1335\tground-truth chords). Beyond reconstruction precision we report\n1336\tYang–Lerch distribution-overlap metrics [36] for pitch (𝐷𝑃 ), dura-\n1337\ttion (𝐷𝐷 ), and inter-onset interval (IOI), plus chord-tone accuracy\n1338\t(CTA). TagFill leads reconstruction precision by ∼10× (bme) and\n1339\t∼4.6× (nf1) and is better on 𝐷𝑃 and CTA, while Polyffusion pro-\n1340\tduces more natural onset timing (Table 8): editing precisely recon-\n1341\tstructs target content, diffusion generates distributionally natural\n1342\ttiming. Given ground-truth chords, Polyffusion’s CTA rises to .725,\n1343\tabove the GT level of .681, as reference chords are supplied directly.\n1344\tVariable-gap infilling: calibrating the boundary. To quan-\n1345\ttify where editing yields to generation, we extend this setting to\n1346\tvariable gaps: keep the melody and flanking accompaniment, mask\n1347\t𝑁 interior bars (𝑁 =4 to 16; 𝑁 =16 leaves no source accompaniment\n1348\t\n1349\tat all), and compute metrics only inside the gap. Degradation is two-\n1350\tphase. Reconstruction precision decreases monotonically—bme/nf1\n1351\tfall from .100/.349 at 𝑁 =4 to .051/.212 at 𝑁 =14 and .041/.095 at\n1352\t𝑁 =16, with paired Wilcoxon tests (Holm-corrected) significant for\n1353\tboth 𝑁 =8→14 and 𝑁 =14→16. Distributional quality, in contrast, is\n1354\tstable whenever any source context remains (𝐷𝑃 at .88–.93 for all\n1355\t𝑁 ≤14), then collapses from .878 to .623 at 𝑁 =16 (highly significant)—\n1356\texactly when the last source content disappears. This statistically\n1357\tcalibrates the boundary suggested at L4 (Table 5b): with no draft to\n1358\tedit, the task reverts to generation.\n1359\t\n1360\t4.8 Discussion\n1361\tMethod–task complementarity and edit boundary. At L4 (near-\n1362\tcomplete rewriting), all editing methods drop sharply to 0.045–0.090\n1363\tbeat exact match (Table 5b), and when accompaniment is removed\n1364\tentirely they collapse to 0.000: the paradigm’s core advantage—\n1365\tpreserving correct context—ceases to apply once no source survives.\n1366\tWe also tested a track-aware attention bias variant, which decreased\n1367\tperformance (Appendix L), suggesting shared attention already\n1368\tcaptures inter-track relationships without explicit structural bias.\n1369\tEncoding–method interaction effects. The significant impact\n1370\tof encoding choice (§4.4) extends beyond editing methods to gener-\n1371\tative baselines: Diffusion exhibits extreme scheme dependence (D:\n1372\t0.390 vs. A: 0.093 on correction), and AR-Prompt scores at most 0.15\n1373\tregardless of scheme. As a practical guideline, relative-separated en-\n1374\tcoding (Scheme B) is viable for single-pass classification, but should\n1375\tbe avoided for iterative or generative pipelines where cascading\n1376\terrors compound across rounds.\n1377\t\n1378\tEdit localization as the AR bottleneck. We evaluate four\n1379\tAR (LLaMA) strategies with increasing positional guidance (Ap-\n1380\tpendix I.1). Performance scales monotonically with guidance: on\n1381\tediting, beat exact match rises from 0.095 (Prompt, no guidance)\n1382\tthrough 0.278 (Detect, SeqTag’s error detector) to 0.499 (Selective,\n1383\toracle positions). Notably, Teacher and Prompt perform compara-\n1384\tbly, suggesting that knowing the melody matters less than knowing\n1385\twhere to edit. Even with oracle positions, AR-Selective remains far\n1386\tbehind edit-based methods on correction (0.477 vs. 0.726), indicating\n1387\tthat AR generation cannot replicate per-token editing precision.\n1388\t\n1389\tPre-training and architecture. Ablations (Appendix L) iden-\n1390\ttify two critical design choices. First, removing BERT pre-training\n1391\tdegrades all tasks substantially (correction: 0.700→0.195), whereas\n1392\tthe S1-only variant without task-specific fine-tuning stays compa-\n1393\trable (0.719 vs. 0.700), indicating pre-trained representations are\n1394\tthe primary driver. Second, replacing the encoder-only architecture\n1395\twith an encoder-decoder causes performance to collapse, confirm-\n1396\ting that shared bidirectional attention over both edited and context\n1397\ttokens is essential.\n1398\t\n1399\tInference efficiency. Table 9 reports latency ranges across all\n1400\tthree tasks. Single-pass methods (SeqTag, TagFill, BERT-CMLM)\n1401\tare stable at 37–65 ms regardless of task, two orders of magnitude\n1402\tfaster than AR; IterEdit varies with task complexity (82–655 ms), an\n1403\torder of magnitude faster than AR. Per-encoding analysis and an\n1404\tarchitecture-agnostic FLOPs estimate (Appendix O) further show\n1405\tthat bundled encodings are 35–40% faster due to shorter sequences,\n1406\tand that the speed gap is paradigmatic rather than implementa-\n1407\ttional.\n1408\t\n1409\t\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n1410\t\n1411\tACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n1412\t\n1413\tTable 9: Inference latency across tasks (ms).\n1414\t\n1415\tMethod\n1416\t\n1417\tLatency (ms)\n1418\t\n1419\tParams (M)\n1420\t\n1421\tBERT-CMLM\n1422\tSeqTag\n1423\tTagFill\n1424\tIterEdit\n1425\tDiffusion\n1426\tAR\n1427\t\n1428\t37–42\n1429\t57–65\n1430\t60\n1431\t82–655\n1432\t434–484\n1433\t9,357–23,654\n1434\t\n1435\t30.2\n1436\t37.2\n1437\t63.8\n1438\t33.9\n1439\t34.4\n1440\t162.0\n1441\t\n1442\t5 Related Work\n1443\t5.1 Symbolic Music Generation and\n1444\t\n1445\tRepresentation\n1446\t\n1447\tSymbolic music generation is dominated by two paradigms. Au-\n1448\ttoregressive Transformers [13, 18, 27, 33] treat symbolic music as\n1449\ta flat sequence of discrete tokens—encoding pitch, duration, ve-\n1450\tlocity, and timing as interleaved events—generated left-to-right.\n1451\tDiffusion models [14, 23] instead operate over grid-based repre-\n1452\tsentations where pitch and time form a two-dimensional matrix,\n1453\titeratively denoising from random noise toward coherent struc-\n1454\tture. Both paradigms are tightly coupled with their underlying\n1455\ttokenization, making music representation a critical design deci-\n1456\tsion. REMI [15] uses multi-token note events, CPWord [12] groups\n1457\tattributes into composites, and Beat [28] proposes beat-anchored\n1458\ttokenization with ternary patterns. Systematic evaluations [7, 8, 38]\n1459\tconfirm that tokenization choices significantly affect generation\n1460\tquality, with further work on compact multi-track encodings [6]\n1461\treinforcing this finding.\n1462\t\n1463\t5.2 Edit-Based Generation\n1464\t\n1465\tEdit-based methods predict explicit per-position operations to trans-\n1466\tform an input sequence, structurally preserving unedited content.\n1467\tIn natural language processing, this paradigm takes several forms:\n1468\tGECToR [24] frames grammatical error correction as token-level\n1469\ttagging, LaserTagger [21] combines KEEP/DELETE decisions with\n1470\tinsertion phrases, the Levenshtein Transformer [9] performs iter-\n1471\tative deletion and insertion, and Felix [20] decomposes rewriting\n1472\tinto tagging followed by filling; extensions include parallel iter-\n1473\tative editing [2] and instruction-tuned models spanning diverse\n1474\tedit types [30]. Beyond text, the same principle has been applied to\n1475\tcode bug fixing [5] and molecular optimization via graph-to-graph\n1476\ttranslation [16].\n1477\t\n1478\t5.3 Music Editing\n1479\t\n1480\tExisting approaches to music editing are predominantly generative.\n1481\tMusic inpainting [26] fills masked regions via conditional gener-\n1482\tation, with extensions to variable-length infilling [3], interactive\n1483\trefinement [11], and multi-level control [10]. In the diffusion para-\n1484\tdigm, SDEdit [22] performs noise-then-denoise editing, GETMu-\n1485\tsic [19] adopts discrete diffusion with a unified track-conditional\n1486\trepresentation for flexible multi-track generation, and cascaded\n1487\tdiffusion models [35] decompose whole-song synthesis into hierar-\n1488\tchical inpainting stages. Text-guided methods have also emerged:\n1489\tMusicMagus [39] manipulates diffusion latent spaces via textual\n1490\tinstructions, and AUDIT [34] edits audio with latent diffusion\n1491\t\n1492\tguided by natural language. While promising, these methods oper-\n1493\tate through implicit conditional generation rather than predicting\n1494\texplicit per-position edit operations at the symbolic sequence level.\n1495\t\n1496\t6 Conclusion\n1497\t\n1498\tThis work demonstrates that edit-based methods are effective for\n1499\tsymbolic music generation, achieving higher precision and percep-\n1500\ttual quality than autoregressive and diffusion baselines across error\n1501\tcorrection, accompaniment editing, and segment completion, with\n1502\tsingle-pass inference under 100 ms. Our cross-factorial analysis\n1503\treveals encoding design as a critical, previously overlooked per-\n1504\tformance lever: effective editing requires atomic edit units, trivial\n1505\tsource–target alignment, and bounded edit locality, and encoding\n1506\tchoice can rival method choice, with significant encoding–method\n1507\tinteraction effects. The three mechanisms specialize complementar-\n1508\tily along the edit-density axis—sequence tagging for sparse correc-\n1509\ttions, iterative refinement for medium-density editing, tag-then-fill\n1510\tfor segment completion—while performance degrades sharply un-\n1511\tder near-complete rewriting, delineating a principled boundary\n1512\twhere editing yields to generation.\n1513\t\n1514\tOur experiments rely on synthetically perturbed data. While this\n1515\tsimplifies evaluation by allowing precise control over task difficulty\n1516\tand perturbation ratios, it does not fully capture the diversity of\n1517\treal-world music editing, where drafts are revised, arrangements\n1518\tvaried, and styles adapted. This gap is field-wide: paired draft-\n1519\tto-final corpora do not yet exist for music, and corrupting clean\n1520\ttargets to construct training pairs is standard in edit-based NLP\n1521\t(GECToR [24] pre-trains on ∼9M synthetically corrupted sentences;\n1522\tPIE [2] uses programmatically perturbed text). The current setting\n1523\talso fixes 𝜏 = 4, assumes given beat/bar boundaries, and omits\n1524\tvelocity—constraints of the controlled evaluation rather than of\n1525\tthe paradigm: boundaries can come from standard beat-tracking\n1526\ttools at deployment, and velocity is an orthogonal pattern channel\n1527\teditable by the same per-token operations. We hope this work\n1528\tmotivates the community to build large-scale paired datasets of\n1529\tgenuine compositional edits, advancing methods and tasks that\n1530\treflect how music is actually created and refined.\n1531\t\n1532\tAcknowledgments\n1533\t\n1534\tThis work was supported in part by the GJYC program of Guangzhou\n1535\tunder Grant 2024D01J0081, in part by the ZJ program of Guangdong\n1536\tunder Grant 2023QN10X455, and in part by the Fundamental Re-\n1537\tsearch Funds for the Central Universities under Grant 2025ZYGXZR053.\n1538\t\n1539\tReferences\n1540\t[1] Jacob Austin, Daniel D. Johnson, Jonathan Ho, Daniel Tarlow, and Rianne van den\n1541\tBerg. 2021. Structured Denoising Diffusion Models in Discrete State-Spaces. In\n1542\tAdvances in Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS), Vol. 34.\n1543\t\n1544\t[2] Abhijeet Awasthi, Sunita Sarawagi, Rasna Goyal, Sabyasachi Ghosh, and Vihari\n1545\tPiratla. 2019. Parallel Iterative Edit Models for Local Sequence Transduction. In\n1546\tProceedings of the 2019 Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language Pro-\n1547\tcessing and the 9th International Joint Conference on Natural Language Processing\n1548\t(EMNLP-IJCNLP). Association for Computational Linguistics, 4260–4270.\n1549\t\n1550\t[3] Chin-Jui Chang, Chun-Yi Lee, and Yi-Hsuan Yang. 2021. Variable-Length Mu-\n1551\tsic Score Infilling via XLNet and Musically Specialized Positional Encoding.\n1552\tIn Proceedings of the 22nd International Society for Music Information Retrieval\n1553\tConference (ISMIR). 97–104.\n1554\t\n1555\t[4] Jacob Devlin, Ming-Wei Chang, Kenton Lee, and Kristina Toutanova. 2019. BERT:\n1556\tPre-training of Deep Bidirectional Transformers for Language Understanding. In\n1557\tProceedings of the 2019 Conference of the North American Chapter of the Association\n1558\t\n1559\t\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n1560\t\n1561\tHaoyu Gu et al.\n1562\t\n1563\tComputing and Applications 32 (2020), 955–967. doi:10.1007/s00521-018-3758-9\n1564\t[26] Ashis Pati, Alexander Lerch, and Gaëtan Hadjeres. 2019. Learning to Traverse\n1565\tLatent Spaces for Musical Score Inpainting. In Proceedings of the 20th International\n1566\tSociety for Music Information Retrieval Conference (ISMIR). 343–351.\n1567\t\n1568\t[27] Christine Payne. 2019. MuseNet. OpenAI Blog. https://openai.com/index/\n1569\t\n1570\tmusenet/\n1571\t\n1572\t[28] Lekai Qian, Haoyu Gu, Jingwei Zhao, and Ziyu Wang. 2026. BEAT: Tokenizing\n1573\tand Generating Symbolic Music by Uniform Temporal Steps. In International\n1574\tConference on Machine Learning (ICML).\n1575\t\n1576\t[29] Colin Raffel. 2016. Learning-Based Methods for Comparing Sequences, with Appli-\n1577\tcations to Audio-to-MIDI Alignment and Matching. Ph. D. Dissertation. Columbia\n1578\tUniversity.\n1579\t\n1580\t[30] Vipul Raheja, Dhruv Kumar, Ryan Koo, and Dongyeop Kang. 2023. CoEdIT:\n1581\tText Editing by Task-Specific Instruction Tuning. In Findings of the Associa-\n1582\ttion for Computational Linguistics: EMNLP 2023. Association for Computational\n1583\tLinguistics, 5274–5291.\n1584\t\n1585\t[31] Jan Retkowski, Jakub Stępniak, and Mateusz Modrzejewski. 2024. Fréchet\n1586\tMusic Distance: A Metric for Generative Symbolic Music Evaluation.\n1587\tarXiv:2412.07948 [cs.SD] https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.07948\n1588\t\n1589\t[32] John Thickstun, David Hall, Chris Donahue, and Percy Liang. 2024. Anticipa-\n1590\ttory Music Transformer. In International Conference on Learning Representations\n1591\t(ICLR).\n1592\t\n1593\t[33] Dimitri von Rütte, Luca Biggio, Yannic Kilcher, and Thomas Hofmann. 2023.\n1594\tFIGARO: Controllable Music Generation using Learned and Expert Features. In\n1595\tInternational Conference on Learning Representations (ICLR).\n1596\t\n1597\t[34] Yuancheng Wang, Zeqian Ju, Xu Tan, Lei He, Zhizheng Wu, Jiang Bian, and\n1598\tSheng Zhao. 2023. AUDIT: Audio Editing by Following Instructions with La-\n1599\ttent Diffusion Models. In Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems 36\n1600\t(NeurIPS).\n1601\t\n1602\t[35] Ziyu Wang, Lejun Min, and Gus Xia. 2024. Whole-Song Hierarchical Generation\n1603\tof Symbolic Music Using Cascaded Diffusion Models. In Proceedings of the Twelfth\n1604\tInternational Conference on Learning Representations (ICLR).\n1605\t\n1606\t[36] Li-Chia Yang and Alexander Lerch. 2020. On the Evaluation of Generative Models\n1607\t\n1608\tin Music. Neural Computing and Applications 32 (2020), 4773–4784.\n1609\t\n1610\t[37] Mingliang Zeng, Xu Tan, Rui Wang, Zeqian Ju, Tao Qin, and Tie-Yan Liu. 2021.\n1611\tMusicBERT: Symbolic Music Understanding with Large-Scale Pre-Training. In\n1612\tFindings of the Association for Computational Linguistics: ACL-IJCNLP 2021. Asso-\n1613\tciation for Computational Linguistics, 791–800.\n1614\t\n1615\t[38] Huan Zhang, Emmanouil Karystinaios, Simon Dixon, Gerhard Widmer, and\n1616\tCarlos Eduardo Cancino-Chacón. 2023. Symbolic Music Representations for Clas-\n1617\tsification Tasks: A Systematic Evaluation. In Proceedings of the 24th International\n1618\tSociety for Music Information Retrieval Conference (ISMIR). 848–858.\n1619\t\n1620\t[39] Yixiao Zhang, Yukara Ikemiya, Gus Xia, Naoki Murata, Marco A. Martínez-\n1621\tRamírez, Wei-Hsiang Liao, Yuki Mitsufuji, and Simon Dixon. 2024. MusicMagus:\n1622\tZero-Shot Text-to-Music Editing via Diffusion Models. In Proceedings of the\n1623\tThirty-Third International Joint Conference on Artificial Intelligence (IJCAI). 7805–\n1624\t7813.\n1625\t\n1626\tfor Computational Linguistics: Human Language Technologies, Volume 1 (Long and\n1627\tShort Papers). Association for Computational Linguistics, 4171–4186.\n1628\t\n1629\t[5] Elizabeth Dinella, Hanjun Dai, Ziyang Li, Mayur Naik, Le Song, and Ke Wang.\n1630\t2020. Hoppity: Learning Graph Transformations to Detect and Fix