n1940\tMasking\n1941\tBatch size / Epochs\n1942\tOptimizer / Schedule\n1943\t\n1944\t192,788 pieces (154K / 19.3K / 19.3K split)\n1945\t15% of music tokens\n1946\t256 effective / 30\n1947\tAdamW, lr 10−4, cosine + 10% warmup\n1948\t\n1949\tC Music BERT Pre-Training Details\n1950\t\n1951\tThe Music BERT encoder uses the architecture specified in Table 12.\n1952\tPre-training uses standard MLM: 15% of music tokens are selected,\n1953\tof which 80% are replaced with [MASK], 10% with a random music\n1954\ttoken, and 10% left unchanged. Control tokens (IDs ≥ 169) are\n1955\tnever masked. Data augmentation applies random transposition\n1956\t(±5 semitones) with 70% probability; sequences exceeding 2,048\n1957\ttokens are randomly truncated.\n1958\t\n1959\tTraining dynamics. Best validation losses (across all epochs)\n1960\tvary across encoding schemes: Scheme B achieves the lowest loss\n1961\t(0.224, perplexity 1.25), followed by A (0.282, ppl 1.33), C (0.449,\n1962\tppl 1.57), and D (0.502, ppl 1.65). The lower perplexity of separated\n1963\t\n1964\t\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n1965\t\n1966\tHaoyu Gu et al.\n1967\t\n1968\tAlgorithm 2 Beat Decoding (Single-Track)\n1969\tRequire: Token sequence E, steps per beat 𝜏\n1970\tEnsure: piano-roll 𝑋 ∈ {0, 1, 2}𝑃 ×𝑇\n1971\t1: Initialize 𝑋 ← 0𝑃 ×𝑇\n1972\t2: 𝑖 ← 0,\n1973\t𝑝prev ← None\n1974\t3: for each token in E do\n1975\tif token is BAR then\n1976\t4:\n1977\t\n1978\tContinue\n1979\t\n1980\telse if token is BEAT then\n1981\t\n1982\t𝑖 ← 𝑖 + 1,\n1983\t\n1984\t𝑝prev ← None\n1985\t\n1986\telse if token is EMPTY_MARKER then\n1987\t\n1988\tContinue\n1989\t\n1990\telse if token is (PIT 𝑑, PAT 𝑠) then\n1991\t\n1992\tif 𝑝prev = None then\n1993\t\n1994\t𝑝 ← 𝑑 {Absolute pitch (first in beat)}\n1995\t\n1996\telse\n1997\t\n1998\t𝑝 ← 𝑝prev + 𝑑 {Relative pitch}\n1999\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "a6c26182-3b6c-4097-bc3f-bca74a622107", "uuid": "70f8283d-db81-439f-bbf0-fad5e67d101a", "timestamp": "2026-07-14T08:06:18.429Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/beatedit_full.txt", "content": ".013\n\n.084\n\n.889\n\n.930\n\n.945\n\n.725\n\n1747\n\nmetrics exhibit systematic shifts: beat exact match is lower, reflect-\ning the denser merged voices and greater harmonic complexity of\nensemble arrangements, while note-level metrics are higher (nf1\n.531→.797 on correction), indicating that musical content is still\ncaptured under the shift. These results preliminarily show that\nthe framework transfers to multi-instrument settings without ar-\nchitectural modification; a comprehensive evaluation across many\nheterogeneous tracks and instrument roles remains future work.\nDetails are provided in Appendix P.\n\n4.7 External Comparison and the\nEditing–Generation Boundary\n\nComparison with Polyffusion. We compare TagFill against the\ndiffusion model Polyffusion [23] on segment completion over its\nhome dataset POP909 (4/4 pieces; song-level split: 161 train / 20\ntest songs, 204 eight-bar segments): given the melody and flanking\naccompaniment, fill four interior bars. The setup is conservative for\nus—Polyffusion’s official checkpoint was trained on all of POP909\nincluding our test songs, whereas TagFill fine-tunes its inserter\nonly on the training split—and both receive equal information (no\nground-truth chords). Beyond reconstruction precision we report\nYang–Lerch distribution-overlap metrics [36] for pitch (𝐷𝑃 ), dura-\ntion (𝐷𝐷 ), and inter-onset interval (IOI), plus chord-tone accuracy\n(CTA). TagFill leads reconstruction precision by ∼10× (bme) and\n∼4.6× (nf1) and is better on 𝐷𝑃 and CTA, while Polyffusion pro-\nduces more natural onset timing (Table 8): editing precisely recon-\nstructs target content, diffusion generates distributionally natural\ntiming. Given ground-truth chords, Polyffusion’s CTA rises to .725,\nabove the GT level of .681, as reference chords are supplied directly.\nVariable-gap infilling: calibrating the boundary. To quan-\ntify where editing yields to generation, we extend this setting to\nvariable gaps: keep the melody and flanking accompaniment, mask\n𝑁 interior bars (𝑁 =4 to 16; 𝑁 =16 leaves no source accompaniment\n\nat all), and compute metrics only inside the gap. Degradation is two-\nphase. Reconstruction precision decreases monotonically—bme/nf1\nfall from .100/.349 at 𝑁 =4 to .051/.212 at 𝑁 =14 and .041/.095 at\n𝑁 =16, with paired Wilcoxon tests (Holm-corrected) significant for\nboth 𝑁 =8→14 and 𝑁 =14→16. Distributional quality, in contrast, is\nstable whenever any source context remains (𝐷𝑃 at .88–.93 for all\n𝑁 ≤14), then collapses from .878 to .623 at 𝑁 =16 (highly significant)—\nexactly when the last source content disappears. This statistically\ncalibrates the boundary suggested at L4 (Table 5b): with no draft to\nedit, the task reverts to generation.\n\n4.8 Discussion\nMethod–task complementarity and edit boundary. At L4 (near-\ncomplete rewriting), all editing methods drop sharply to 0.045–0.090\nbeat exact match (Table 5b), and when accompaniment is removed\nentirely they collapse to 0.000: the paradigm’s core advantage—\npreserving correct context—ceases to apply once no source survives.\nWe also tested a track-aware attention bias variant, which decreased\nperformance (Appendix L), suggesting shared attention already\ncaptures inter-track relationships without explicit structural bias.\nEncoding–method interaction effects. The significant impact\nof encoding choice (§4.4) extends beyond editing methods to gener-\native baselines: Diffusion exhibits extreme scheme dependence (D:\n0.390 vs. A: 0.093 on correction), and AR-Prompt scores at most 0.15\nregardless of scheme. As a practical guideline, relative-separated en-\ncoding (Scheme B) is viable for single-pass classification, but should\nbe avoided for iterative or generative pipelines where cascading\nerrors compound across rounds.\n\nEdit localization as the AR bottleneck. We evaluate four\nAR (LLaMA) strategies with increasing positional guidance (Ap-\npendix I.1). Performance scales monotonically with guidance: on\nediting, beat exact match rises from 0.095 (Prompt, no guidance)\nthrough 0.278 (Detect, SeqTag’s error detector) to 0.499 (Selective,\noracle positions). Notably, Teacher and Prompt perform compara-\nbly, suggesting that knowing the melody matters less than knowing\nwhere to edit. Even with oracle positions, AR-Selective remains far\nbehind edit-based methods on correction (0.477 vs. 0.726), indicating\nthat AR generation cannot replicate per-token editing precision.\n\nPre-training and architecture. Ablations (Appendix L) iden-\ntify two critical design choices. First, removing BERT pre-training\ndegrades all tasks substantially (correction: 0.700→0.195), whereas\nthe S1-only variant without task-specific fine-tuning stays compa-\nrable (0.719 vs. 0.700), indicating pre-trained representations are\nthe primary driver. Second, replacing the encoder-only architecture\nwith an encoder-decoder causes performance to collapse, confirm-\ning that shared bidirectional attention over both edited and context\ntokens is essential.\n\nInference efficiency. Table 9 reports latency ranges across all\nthree tasks. Single-pass methods (SeqTag, TagFill, BERT-CMLM)\nare stable at 37–65 ms regardless of task, two orders of magnitude\nfaster than AR; IterEdit varies with task complexity (82–655 ms), an\norder of magnitude faster than AR. Per-encoding analysis and an\narchitecture-agnostic FLOPs estimate (Appendix O) further show\nthat bundled encodings are 35–40% faster due to shorter sequences,\nand that the speed gap is paradigmatic rather than implementa-\ntional.\n\n\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n\nACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nTable 9: Inference latency across tasks (ms).\n\nMethod\n\nLatency (ms)\n\nParams (M)\n\nBERT-CMLM\nSeqTag\nTagFill\nIterEdit\nDiffusion\nAR\n\n37–42\n57–65\n60\n82–655\n434–484\n9,357–23,654\n\n30.2\n37.2\n63.8\n33.9\n34.4\n162.0\n\n5 Related Work\n5.1 Symbolic Music Generation and\n\nRepresentation\n\nSymbolic music generation is dominated by two paradigms. Au-\ntoregressive Transformers [13, 18, 27, 33] treat symbolic music as\na flat sequence of discrete tokens—encoding pitch, duration, ve-\nlocity, and timing as interleaved events—generated left-to-right.\nDiffusion models [14, 23] instead operate over grid-based repre-\nsentations where pitch and time form a two-dimensional matrix,\niteratively denoising from random noise toward coherent struc-\nture. Both paradigms are tightly coupled with their underlying\ntokenization, making music representation a critical design deci-\nsion. REMI [15] uses multi-token note events, CPWord [12] groups\nattributes into composites, and Beat [28] proposes beat-anchored\ntokenization with ternary patterns. Systematic evaluations [7, 8, 38]\nconfirm that tokenization choices significantly affect generation\nquality, with further work on compact multi-track encodings [6]\nreinforcing this finding.\n\n5.2 Edit-Based Generation\n\nEdit-based methods predict explicit per-position operations to trans-\nform an input sequence, structurally preserving unedited content.\nIn natural language processing, this paradigm takes several forms:\nGECToR [24] frames grammatical error correction as token-level\ntagging, LaserTagger [21] combines KEEP/DELETE decisions with\ninsertion phrases, the Levenshtein Transformer [9] performs iter-\native deletion and insertion, and Felix [20] decomposes rewriting\ninto tagging followed by filling; extensions include parallel iter-\native editing [2] and instruction-tuned models spanning diverse\nedit types [30]. Beyond text, the same principle has been applied to\ncode bug fixing [5] and molecular optimization via graph-to-graph\ntranslation [16].\n\n5.3 Music Editing\n\nExisting approaches to music editing are predominantly generative.\nMusic inpainting [26] fills masked regions via conditional gener-\nation, with extensions to variable-length infilling [3], interactive\nrefinement [11], and multi-level control [10]. In the diffusion para-\ndigm, SDEdit [22] performs noise-then-denoise editing, GETMu-\nsic [19] adopts discrete diffusion with a unified track-conditional\nrepresentation for flexible multi-track generation, and cascaded\ndiffusion models [35] decompose whole-song synthesis into hierar-\nchical inpainting stages. Text-guided methods have also emerged:\nMusicMagus [39] manipulates diffusion latent spaces via textual\ninstructions, and AUDIT [34] edits audio with latent diffusion\n\nguided by natural language. While promising, these methods oper-\nate through implicit conditional generation rather than predicting\nexplicit per-position edit operations at the symbolic sequence level.\n\n6 Conclusion\n\nThis work demonstrates that edit-based methods are effective for\nsymbolic music generation, achieving higher precision and percep-\ntual quality than autoregressive and diffusion baselines across error\ncorrection, accompaniment editing, and segment completion, with\nsingle-pass inference under 100 ms. Our cross-factorial analysis\nreveals encoding design as a critical, previously overlooked per-\nformance lever: effective editing requires atomic edit units, trivial\nsource–target alignment, and bounded edit locality, and encoding\nchoice can rival method choice, with significant encoding–method\ninteraction effects. The three mechanisms specialize complementar-\nily along the edit-density axis—sequence tagging for sparse correc-\ntions, iterative refinement for medium-density editing, tag-then-fill\nfor segment completion—while performance degrades sharply un-\nder near-complete rewriting, delineating a principled boundary\nwhere editing yields to generation.\n\nOur experiments rely on synthetically perturbed data. While this\nsimplifies evaluation by allowing precise control over task difficulty\nand perturbation ratios, it does not fully capture the diversity of\nreal-world music editing, where drafts are revised, arrangements\nvaried, and styles adapted. This gap is field-wide: paired draft-\nto-final corpora do not yet exist for music, and corrupting clean\ntargets to construct training pairs is standard in edit-based NLP\n(GECToR [24] pre-trains on ∼9M synthetically corrupted sentences;\nPIE [2] uses programmatically perturbed text). The current setting\nalso fixes 𝜏 = 4, assumes given beat/bar boundaries, and omits\nvelocity—constraints of the controlled evaluation rather than of\nthe paradigm: boundaries can come from standard beat-tracking\ntools at deployment, and velocity is an orthogonal pattern channel\neditable by the same per-token operations. We hope this work\nmotivates the community to build large-scale paired datasets of\ngenuine compositional edits, advancing methods and tasks that\nreflect how music is actually created and refined.\n\nAcknowledgments\n\nThis work was supported in part by the GJYC program of Guangzhou\nunder Grant 2024D01J0081, in part by the ZJ program of Guangdong\nunder Grant 2023QN10X455, and in part by the Fundamental Re-\nsearch Funds for the Central Universities under Grant 2025ZYGXZR053.\n\nReferences\n[1] Jacob Austin, Daniel D. Johnson, Jonathan Ho, Daniel Tarlow, and Rianne van den\nBerg. 2021. Structured Denoising Diffusion Models in Discrete State-Spaces. In\nAdvances in Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS), Vol. 34.\n\n[2] Abhijeet Awasthi, Sunita Sarawagi, Rasna Goyal, Sabyasachi Ghosh, and Vihari\nPiratla. 2019. Parallel Iterative Edit Models for Local Sequence Transduction. In\nProceedings of the 2019 Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language Pro-\ncessing and the 9th International Joint Conference on Natural Language Processing\n(EMNLP-IJCNLP). Association for Computational Linguistics, 4260–4270.\n\n[3] Chin-Jui Chang, Chun-Yi Lee, and Yi-Hsuan Yang. 2021. Variable-Length Mu-\nsic Score Infilling via XLNet and Musically Specialized Positional Encoding.\nIn Proceedings of the 22nd International Society for Music Information Retrieval\nConference (ISMIR). 97–104.\n\n[4] Jacob Devlin, Ming-Wei Chang, Kenton Lee, and Kristina Toutanova. 2019. BERT:\nPre-training of Deep Bidirectional Transformers for Language Understanding. In\nProceedings of the 2019 Conference of the North American Chapter of the Association\n\n\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nHaoyu Gu et al.\n\nComputing and Applications 32 (2020), 955–967. doi:10.1007/s00521-018-3758-9\n[26] Ashis Pati, Alexander Lerch, and Gaëtan Hadjeres. 2019. Learning to Traverse\nLatent Spaces for Musical Score Inpainting. In Proceedings of the 20th International\nSociety for Music Information Retrieval Conference (ISMIR). 343–351.\n\n[27] Christine Payne. 2019. MuseNet. OpenAI Blog. https://openai.com/index/\n\nmusenet/\n\n[28] Lekai Qian, Haoyu Gu, Jingwei Zhao, and Ziyu Wang. 2026. BEAT: Tokenizing\nand Generating Symbolic Music by Uniform Temporal Steps. In International\nConference on Machine Learning (ICML).\n\n[29] Colin Raffel. 2016. Learning-Based Methods for Comparing Sequences, with Appli-\ncations to Audio-to-MIDI Alignment and Matching. Ph. D. Dissertation. Columbia\nUniversity.\n\n[30] Vipul Raheja, Dhruv Kumar, Ryan Koo, and Dongyeop Kang. 2023. CoEdIT:\nText Editing by Task-Specific Instruction Tuning. In Findings of the Associa-\ntion for Computational Linguistics: EMNLP 2023. Association for Computational\nLinguistics, 5274–5291.\n\n[31] Jan Retkowski, Jakub Stępniak, and Mateusz Modrzejewski. 2024. Fréchet\nMusic Distance: A Metric for Generative Symb