yEdits(𝑋, 𝑡)\n2197\t𝑋 ← Decode-Filter-Reencode(𝑋 ) {validity check}\n2198\tif all 𝑡𝑖 = KEEP then\n2199\t\n2200\tbreak\n2201\t\n2202\tend if\n2203\t9:\n2204\t10: end for\n2205\t11: return 𝑋\n2206\t\n2207\torder, which also repairs any ordering violations. A beat that fails\n2208\t\n2209\t\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n2210\t\n2211\tACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n2212\t\n2213\tto parse is left unchanged, and beats outside the edited region re-\n2214\tassemble verbatim, so the cycle guarantees a well-formed input for\n2215\tthe next iteration without perturbing untouched content.\n2216\t\n2217\tF End-to-End Error Correction Walkthrough\n2218\t\n2219\tWe trace a correction involving two error types—a pitch shift and a\n2220\tmissing note—through the full pipeline under Scheme B (relative,\n2221\tseparated). Consider a beat whose target is C4–E4–G4 as quarter\n2222\tnotes (pattern token 53, Appendix A). The input has C4 shifted to\n2223\tD4 (+2 semitones) and G4 missing.\n2224\t\n2225\tStep 1: Encoding. The target and corrupted input are:\n2226\t\n2227\tTarget\n2228\t\n2229\tInput\n2230\t\n2231\t[120][53] [85][53] [84][53]\n2232\t(C4, E4, G4 as quarter notes)\n2233\t[122][53] [83][53]\n2234\t(D4, E4 only—G4 missing)\n2235\t\n2236\tD4 yields position 81 + 41 = 122; the relative distance from D4 to\n2237\tE4 is 2 (token 83).\n2238\t\n2239\tStep 2: Iteration 1—pitch correction via SHIFT. The model\n2240\t\n2241\t3:\n2242\t\n2243\t4:\n2244\t\n2245\t5:\n2246\t\n2247\tdetects the pitch error and predicts:\n2248\t\n2249\tTable 16: Perturbation types for synthetic error data. Per-\n2250\tbeat, mutually exclusive.\n2251\t\n2252\tType\n2253\t\n2254\tOperation\n2255\t\n2256\tProb. Constraint\n2257\t\n2258\tPitch shift\n2259\tRhythm change\n2260\tNote deletion\n2261\tNote insertion\n2262\tNo change\n2263\t\n2264\t𝑝 𝑗 ← 𝑝 𝑗 + Uniform(±1–3)\n2265\t𝑠 𝑗 ← Random( [0, 80] \\ {𝑠 𝑗 } )\n2266\tRemove one (𝑝 𝑗 , 𝑠 𝑗 ) pair\n2267\tAdd (𝑝new, 𝑠new )\n2268\tIdentity\n2269\t\n2270\t0.10\n2271\t0.05\n2272\t0.03\n2273\t0.02\n2274\t0.80\n2275\t\n2276\tValid range\n2277\t—\n2278\tKeep ≥ 1 note\n2279\tNo duplicates\n2280\t—\n2281\t\n2282\tAlgorithm 4 Iterative editing inference (IterEdit)\n2283\tRequire: Current tokens 𝑋 , editable flags 𝐸, model M, max rounds\n2284\t\n2285\t𝑅max = 10\n2286\t\n2287\t1: for 𝑟 = 1 to 𝑅max do\n2288\t2:\n2289\t\n2290\t// Step 1: Delete low-confidence tokens\n2291\t𝑑 ← Mdel (𝑋 ); remove 𝑋𝑖 where 𝑑𝑖 >0.5 and 𝐸𝑖 =True\n2292\t// Step 2: Insert placeholders at editable gaps\n2293\t𝑛 ← Mins (𝑋 ); insert 𝑛 𝑗 PLH tokens at gap 𝑗 if gap is editable\n2294\t\n2295\tToken\n2296\t\n2297\tLabel\n2298\tResult\n2299\t\n2300\t[122]\n2301\t\n2302\tSHIFT−2\n2303\t[120]\n2304\t\n2305\t[53]\n2306\t\n2307\tKEEP\n2308\t[53]\n2309\t\n2310\t[83]\n2311\t\n2312\t[53]\n2313\t\n2314\tSHIFT+2\n2315\t[85]\n2316\t\n2317\tAPPEND84\n2318\t[53] [84]\n2319\t\n2320\tSHIFT−2 corrects D4→C4; SHIFT+2 fixes the cascading interval to\n2321\tE4; APPEND84 inserts a position token for the missing G4 (81+3 = 84,\n2322\trelative to E4). Since APPEND attaches only one token per anchor, the\n2323\tpattern token for G4 cannot be produced within the same round.\n2324\t\n2325\tStep 3: Post-processing and convergence. The Decode-Filter-\n2326\tReencode step (Appendix E) parses the beat into complete (position,\n2327\tpattern) pairs; the trailing token [84] lacks a pattern token, does\n2328\tnot form a valid note, and is discarded during re-encoding, yield-\n2329\ting [120][53] [85][53]. Both pitch errors are therefore fixed\n2330\twithin a single iteration, while the missing G4 is not restored: even\n2331\tif a later iteration proposes the same APPEND, post-processing re-\n2332\tmoves the incomplete insertion again and the no-progress check\n2333\tterminates inference. This reflects a structural limitation of sep-\n2334\tarated encodings—restoring a deleted note requires two coordi-\n2335\tnated tokens, but validity filtering only admits complete pairs—and\n2336\tis consistent with note deletion being the hardest error type for\n2337\tSchemes A and B (Figure 3). Under bundled encoding the same re-\n2338\tpair is a single edit: in Scheme C the missing G4 corresponds to one\n2339\tcomposite token (3 × 81 + 53 = 296), so APPEND296 completes the in-\n2340\tsertion within one iteration and passes post-processing unchanged.\n2341\tThis walkthrough demonstrates that SHIFT and APPEND cooperate\n2342\twithin a single iteration, and that Decode-Filter-Reencode acts\n2343\tas a structural safety net: every intermediate sequence remains\n2344\twell-formed and decodable, at the cost of discarding insertions left\n2345\tincomplete at the end of an iteration.\n2346\t\n2347\tG Synthetic Perturbation Details\n2348\tH IterEdit Inference Algorithm\n2349\t\n2350\tI Generative Baseline Details\n2351\t\n2352\tThe main text reports summary results for the two generative\n2353\tbaselines; here we provide full per-scheme and per-configuration\n2354\t\n2355\t6: Mark all new PLH positions as editable\n2356\t7:\n2357\t\n2358\t// Step 3: Fill placeholders\n2359\t𝑋𝑖 ← arg max Mtok (𝑋 )𝑖 for each PLH position 𝑖\n2360\tif no deletions, no insertions, and no fills then\n2361\t\n2362\t8:\n2363\t\n2364\t9:\n2365\t\n2366\t10:\n2367\t\n2368\tbreak\n2369\t\n2370\tend if\n2371\t11:\n2372\t12: end for\n2373\t13: return 𝑋\n2374\t\n2375\tbreakdowns that reveal encoding sensitivity patterns consistent\n2376\twith those observed for edit-based methods.\n2377\t\n2378\tI.1 Autoregressive LLM Baseline\n2379\t\n2380\tTo quantify the gap between autoregressive generation and edit-\n2381\tbased paradigms, we evaluate four LLaMA-based strategies (∼162M\n2382\tparameters, trained from scratch on the same data), ordered by the\n2383\tamount of positional guidance provided:\n2384\t• AR-Prompt: takes the first 2 bars of the source as prompt and\n2385\tautoregressively generates the rest; the generated melody is re-\n2386\tplaced with the source melody post hoc.\n2387\t\n2388\t• AR-Teacher: melody beats are fed via teacher-forcing with ex-\n2389\tplicit track markers; all accompaniment beats are regenerated.\n2390\t• AR-Detect: a two-stage pipeline that uses SeqTag’s error detec-\n2391\ttion head to identify perturbed beats (any accompaniment token\n2392\twith 𝑃 (error) ≥ 0.5 flags the beat), then regenerates only those\n2393\tbeats via LLaMA with melody teacher-forcing. This provides the\n2394\tfairest AR comparison, as it uses the same localization signal\n2395\tavailable to edit methods.\n2396\t\n2397\t• AR-Selective: same teacher-forcing as Teacher, but only the\n2398\taccompaniment beats at oracle-known changed_beat_indices\n2399\tare regenerated; unperturbed beats retain the source content.\n2400\tThis is the most favorable setting for AR.\n2401\t\n2402\tImplementation. For Scheme A, melody beats start with Track0 (183)\n2403\tand accompaniment with Track1 (184); Teacher/Selective explicitly\n2404\tinsert 184 before sampling accompaniment content. For bundled\n2405\tschemes (C/D), SPLIT_0 (7129) and SPLIT_1 (7130) serve as track\n2406\t\n2407\t\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n2408\t\n2409\tHaoyu Gu et al.\n2410\t\n2411\tmarkers. For Scheme B (no explicit marker), beats alternate by\n2412\tposition and terminate with END_MARKER (170). Prompt/Full post-\n2413\tprocessing parses the generated sequence into beat pairs and re-\n2414\tplaces melody beats with source melody.\n2415\tFairness note. Edit methods (SeqTag/TagFill/IterEdit) see the com-\n2416\tplete corrupted source and must autonomously identify which\n2417\tpositions need modification. AR-Prompt and AR-Teacher do not\n2418\tknow which beats are perturbed and regenerate all accompaniment.\n2419\tAR-Selective additionally receives oracle changed_beat_indices—\n2420\tinformation unavailable to edit methods. Results for Selective there-\n2421\tfore represent an upper bound on AR performance under ideal\n2422\tlocalization, not a fair head-to-head comparison.\n2423\t\n2424\tTable 17: LLaMA baseline results (𝑛 = 200, perturbed-only).\n2425\tBest per task–strategy in bold. †Selective receives oracle\n2426\tchanged-beat positions.\n2427\t\n2428\tStrategy\n2429\t\n2430\tTask\n2431\t\n2432\tSch.\n2433\t\n2434\tbeat↑\n2435\t\n2436\tnf1↑ MPE↓\n2437\t\n2438\tFMD↓\n2439\t\n2440\tAR-Select.†\n2441\t\n2442\tAR-Detect\n2443\t\n2444\tAR-Teacher\n2445\t\n2446\tAR-Prompt\n2447\t\n2448\tCorr.\n2449\tEdit.\n2450\tCompl.\n2451\t\n2452\tCorr.\n2453\tEdit.\n2454\t\n2455\tCorr.\n2456\tEdit.\n2457\tCompl.\n2458\t\n2459\tCorr.\n2460\tEdit.\n2461\tCompl.\n2462\t\n2463\tA\n2464\tA\n2465\tA\n2466\t\n2467\tA\n2468\tA\n2469\t\n2470\tB\n2471\tA\n2472\tC\n2473\t\n2474\tD\n2475\tA\n2476\tA\n2477\t\n2478\t.477\n2479\t.499\n2480\t.397\n2481\t\n2482\t.394\n2483\t.278\n2484\t\n2485\t.062\n2486\t.101\n2487\t.117\n2488\t\n2489\t.093\n2490\t.095\n2491\t.152\n2492\t\n2493\t.637\n2494\t.603\n2495\t.512\n2496\t\n2497\t.650\n2498\t.478\n2499\t\n2500\t.238\n2501\t.211\n2502\t.221\n2503\t\n2504\t.242\n2505\t.211\n2506\t.221\n2507\t\n2508\t8.6\n2509\t9.6\n2510\t14.4\n2511\t\n2512\t9.1\n2513\t15.2\n2514\t\n2515\t20.0\n2516\t25.6\n2517\t22.6\n2518\t\n2519\t16.3\n2520\t25.8\n2521\t18.7\n2522\t\n2523\t1.17\n2524\t0.85\n2525\t0.39\n2526\t\n2527\t1.24\n2528\t1.73\n2529\t\n2530\t5.74\n2531\t7.07\n2532\t5.82\n2533\t\n2534\t11.2\n2535\t3.89\n2536\t1.54\n2537\t\n2538\tThe results reveal a clear localization hierarchy. Prompt and\n2539\tTeacher, which lack positional guidance, achieve at most 0.152 beat\n2540\texact match. Detect, using SeqTag’s error detector for automated\n2541\tlocalization, jumps to 0.394 on correction and 0.278 on editing—\n2542\ta substantial improvement but still below edit methods (SeqTag:\n2543\t0.726, IterEdit: 0.480). Selective, given oracle positions, reaches\n2544\t0.477–0.499 but still cannot match per-token precision on correction\n2545\t(0.477 vs. 0.726). Detect is inapplicable to completion, as the error\n2546\tdetector cannot identify missing content.\n2547\t\n2548\tThe gap between Detect and edit methods is particularly infor-\n2549\tmative: both use the same localization signal (SeqTag’s detector),\n2550\tbut edit methods apply targeted token-level operations while De-\n2551\ttect regenerates entire beats via AR sampling. This confirms that\n2552\tthe editing mechanism itself—not just localization—is the source of\n2553\tthe performance advantage. Selective consistently favors Scheme A,\n2554\tand its FMD values (0.39–1.17) are competitive with edit methods,\n2555\tsuggesting that AR generation can produce distributionally natural\n2556\toutput at the cost of requiring oracle positional guidance.\n2557\t\n2558\tI.2 Discrete Diffusion Baseline\n2559\t\n2560\tWe evaluate D3PM [1] discrete diffusion (∼34M parameters) with\n2561\tan SDEdit-style noise-then-denoise strategy at three noise ratios:\n2562\t𝑟 =0.3 (30 denoising steps), 𝑟 =0.5 (50 steps), and 𝑟 =0.7 (70 steps). All\n2563\tmodels are trained on the same data with all four encoding schemes\n2564\t(𝑛 = 200, perturbed-only).\n2565\t\n2566\tThree findings are notable. First, performance degrades sharply\n2567\twith noise ratio: 𝑟 =0.3 is the only competitive setting; 𝑟 =0.5 halves\n2568\tbeat exact match, and 𝑟 =0.7 collapses to near-zero on separated\n2569\tencodings (FMD >200, fail rate >93%). This confirms that SDEdit\n2570\trequires minimal noise injection for editing—heavy noise destroys\n2571\tthe structural information that denoising cannot recover. Second,\n2572\tencoding dependence is extreme and mirrors edit methods: bundled\n2573\tschemes (C/D) outperform separated schemes (A/B) by 4–8× on\n2574\tcorrection (r03: Scheme D 0.390 vs. A 0.089). Separated encoding\n2575\tdistributes each note across two tokens; the diffusion process must\n2576\tindependently recover both tokens in a consistent pair, a coordi-\n2577\tnation problem that bundled encoding avoids. This parallel to edit\n2578\tmethods’ encoding sensitivity provides independent evidence that\n2579\tencoding choice is a universal design lever, not method-specific.\n2580\tThird, completion exposes diffusion’s fundamental limitation: Dif-\n2581\tfusion r03 maintains non-trivial beat exact match on completion\n2582\t(0.080) but low nf1 (0.228), and at higher noise ratios (𝑟 =0.5) nf1\n2583\tcollapses to 0.002, indicating that the denoising process recovers\n2584\trhythmic structure but struggles with pitch content. TagFill’s nf1\n2585\tof 0.557 on the same task confirms that explicit generation mecha-\n2586\tnisms are required for content synthesis.\n2587\t\n2588\tJ Cross-Encoding Pre-Training Analysis\n2589\t\n2590\tTable 3 (main paper) reports a recovery metric defined as (nf1 −\n2591\tnf1no-edit)/(1 − nf1no-edit), measuring the fraction of the no-edit\n2592\terror gap closed by the method. Beat achieves ∼5× higher recovery\n2593\tthan alternative encodings. Here we trace this gap to its root cause:\n2594\tencoding structure determines pre-training quality, which cascades\n2595\tinto downstream editing performance.\n2596\t\n2597\tJ.1 MLM Pre-Training Convergence\n2598\t\n2599\tAll four Beat schemes converge to PPL = 1.29–1.83, with relative-\n2600\tseparated (Scheme B) achieving the lowest perplexity (1.29). Bun-\n2601\tdled schemes (C/D) start from much higher initial PPL due to their\n2602\t7,145-token vocabulary but undergo a sharp phase transition around\n2603\tepoch 12–18, ultimately converging within 0.2–0.5 of separated\n2604\tschemes. Among alternative encodings, REMI and Structured con-\n2605\tverge normally (PPL = 1.39, 1.57), while MIDI-Like plateaus at 8.18—\n2606\t5–6× higher—reflecting its flat event-stream structure where inter-\n2607\tleaved NoteOn/NoteOff tokens across all 128 pitches create long-\n2608\trange dependencies that MLM cannot capture. CPWord’s apparent\n2609\tPPL of ∼500 reflects its compound vocabulary structure (joint pre-\n2610\tdiction over 5 factored sub-vocabularies) rather than a failure to\n2611\tlearn; its downstream EditF1 confirms meaningful learning.\n2612\t\n2613\tK Full Per-Scheme Results\n2614\t\n2615\tTables 20 and 21 present the complete per-scheme breakdown for\n2616\tall method–task combinations (perturbed-only, 𝑛 = 200). The main\n2617\ttext (Tables 3 and 4) reports only the best-scheme result per method;\n2618\tthese appendix tables reveal the full encoding sensitivity. IterEdit\n2619\twas evaluated across all four schemes. SeqTag cannot perform\n2620\tsegment completion (no generation head).\n2621\t\n2622\tSeveral patterns emerge. Encoding sensitivity: Scheme B remains\n2623\tthe weakest for TagFill and IterEdit, but SeqTag now achieves its\n2624\thighest correction score on Scheme B (0.726), surpassing all other\n2625\tschemes. TagFill and IterEdit still exhibit sharp B-column drops on\n2626\t\n2627\t\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n2628\t\n2629\tACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n2630\t\n2631\tTable 18: Diffusion baseline results across noise ratios and encoding schemes (𝑛 = 200, perturbed-only). Best scheme per\n2632\tratio–task in bold.\n2633\t\n2634\tError Correction\n2635\t\n2636\tAccomp. Editing\n2637\t\n2638\tSegment Completion\n2639\t\n2640\tRatio Sch. beat\n2641\t\n2642\tnf1\n2643\t\n2644\tFMD fail beat\n2645\t\n2646\tnf1\n2647\t\n2648\tFMD fail beat\n2649\t\n2650\tnf1\n2651\t\n2652\tFMD fail\n2653\t\n2654\t𝑟 =0.3\n2655\t\n2656\t𝑟 =0.5\n2657\t\n2658\t𝑟 =0.7\n2659\t\n2660\tA\n2661\tB\n2662\tC\n2663\tD\n2664\t\n2665\tA\n2666\tB\n2667\tC\n2668\tD\n2669\t\n2670\tA\n2671\tB\n2672\tC\n2673\tD\n2674\t\n2675\t.190\n2676\t.124\n2677\t.515\n2678\t\n2679\t14.1\n2680\t.093\n2681\t17.4\n2682\t.048\n2683\t2.03\n2684\t.340\n2685\t.390 .602 0.87 .04 .198\n2686\t\n2687\t.134\n2688\t.076\n2689\t.075\n2690\t.088\n2691\t.200 .372\n2692\t.411\n2693\t\n2694\t.78\n2695\t.87\n2696\t.07\n2697\t\n2698\t.013\n2699\t.005\n2700\t.294\n2701\t\n2702\t.010\n2703\t.029\n2704\t.010\n2705\t.0