85 vs. 7,145). Training\ntimes range from 4.6h (Scheme D) to 27.3h (Scheme B) on 2 GPUs\n(24GB VRAM each).\n\nD Implementation Details\n\nTable 13: SeqTag configuration.\n\nComponent\n\nHeads\n\nError detector\nTag predictor\nDropout\n\nTraining\n\nConfiguration\n\nLinear(512, 2)\nLinear(512, 350 / 14,258)\n0.1\n\nCold start\nFull fine-tune\nFine-tune lr (BERT / heads)\nBatch size / Precision\nKEEP weight / 𝜆detect\n\n2 epochs, freeze BERT (lr 10−3)\n18 epochs, patience 3\n10−5 / 10−4\n64 effective / fp16\n0.15 / 0.5\n\nInference\n\nMax iterations\nKEEP bias 𝛽 / Error threshold 𝜃\n\n3\n0.3 / 0.5\n\nE SeqTag Inference Algorithm\n\nThe Decode-Filter-Reencode step operates beat by beat: it\ndecodes each beat’s tokens into (pitch, pattern) notes, discards in-\nvalid ones (out-of-range pitches or pattern values, duplicate pitches\nwithin a beat), and re-encodes the remainder in ascending pitch\n\nTable 14: TagFill (tag-then-fill) configuration.\n\nComponent\n\nConfiguration\n\nTagger\n\nArchitecture\nOutput head\nLoss\n\nInserter\n\nArchitecture\nOutput head\nLabel smoothing\nMaskGIT passes 𝑇\n\nTraining (both stages)\n\n8-layer Transformer, 512 hidden\nLinear(512, 11)\nFocal Loss (𝛾 = 2.0)\n\n8-layer Transformer, 512 hidden\nLinear(512, 𝑉 )\n0.1\n2\n\nOptimizer / Schedule\nWeight decay / Epochs\nBatch size\nPerturbation levels\n\nAdamW, lr 10−4, cosine + 10% warmup\n0.01 / 30\n96 effective (32 × 3 accum.)\nL1:30%, L2:30%, L3:25%, L4:15%\n\nTable 15: IterEdit (iterative deletion-insertion) configuration.\n\nComponent\n\nConfiguration\n\nArchitecture\nEncoder\nActivation / Norm\nDeletion head\nInsertion head\nToken head\n\nTraining\n\n8-layer Transformer, 512 hidden, 8 heads\nGELU / Pre-norm\nLinear(512, 2)\nLinear(1024, 21)\nLinear(512, 𝑉 )\n\nOptimizer / Schedule\nWeight decay / Epochs\nBatch size\nLoss\nToken label smoothing\n\nAdamW, lr 3 × 10−4, cosine + 10% warmup\n0.01 / 30\n64 effective (32 × 2 accum.)\nLdel + Lins + Ltok\n0.1\n\nInference\n\nMax iterations\nDeletion threshold\n\n10 (completion) / 3 (editing)\n0.5\n\n3:\n\n4:\n\n5:\n\n6:\n\n7:\n\n8:\n\nAlgorithm 3 Iterative music error correction (SeqTag)\nRequire: Encoded tokens 𝑋 , model M, max rounds 𝑅max = 3\n1: for 𝑟 = 1 to 𝑅max do\n2:\n\n𝑑 ← Mdetect (𝑋 ) {binary error detection}\n𝑡 ← Mtag (𝑋 ) {edit tag prediction}\nGate: 𝑡𝑖 ← KEEP wherever 𝑑𝑖 < 0.5 {conservative KEEP bias}\n\nApply labels: 𝑋 ← ApplyEdits(𝑋, 𝑡)\n𝑋 ← Decode-Filter-Reencode(𝑋 ) {validity check}\nif all 𝑡𝑖 = KEEP then\n\nbreak\n\nend if\n9:\n10: end for\n11: return 𝑋\n\norder, which also repairs any ordering violations. A beat that fails\n\n\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n\nACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nto parse is left unchanged, and beats outside the edited region re-\nassemble verbatim, so the cycle guarantees a well-formed input for\nthe next iteration without perturbing untouched content.\n\nF End-to-End Error Correction Walkthrough\n\nWe trace a correction involving two error types—a pitch shift and a\nmissing note—through the full pipeline under Scheme B (relative,\nseparated). Consider a beat whose target is C4–E4–G4 as quarter\nnotes (pattern token 53, Appendix A). The input has C4 shifted to\nD4 (+2 semitones) and G4 missing.\n\nStep 1: Encoding. The target and corrupted input are:\n\nTarget\n\nInput\n\n[120][53] [85][53] [84][53]\n(C4, E4, G4 as quarter notes)\n[122][53] [83][53]\n(D4, E4 only—G4 missing)\n\nD4 yields position 81 + 41 = 122; the relative distance from D4 to\nE4 is 2 (token 83).\n\nStep 2: Iteration 1—pitch correction via SHIFT. The model\n\n3:\n\n4:\n\n5:\n\ndetects the pitch error and predicts:\n\nTable 16: Perturbation types for synthetic error data. Per-\nbeat, mutually exclusive.\n\nType\n\nOperation\n\nProb. Constraint\n\nPitch shift\nRhythm change\nNote deletion\nNote insertion\nNo change\n\n𝑝 𝑗 ← 𝑝 𝑗 + Uniform(±1–3)\n𝑠 𝑗 ← Random( [0, 80] \\ {𝑠 𝑗 } )\nRemove one (𝑝 𝑗 , 𝑠 𝑗 ) pair\nAdd (𝑝new, 𝑠new )\nIdentity\n\n0.10\n0.05\n0.03\n0.02\n0.80\n\nValid range\n—\nKeep ≥ 1 note\nNo duplicates\n—\n\nAlgorithm 4 Iterative editing inference (IterEdit)\nRequire: Current tokens 𝑋 , editable flags 𝐸, model M, max rounds\n\n𝑅max = 10\n\n1: for 𝑟 = 1 to 𝑅max do\n2:\n\n// Step 1: Delete low-confidence tokens\n𝑑 ← Mdel (𝑋 ); remove 𝑋𝑖 where 𝑑𝑖 >0.5 and 𝐸𝑖 =True\n// Step 2: Insert placeholders at editable gaps\n𝑛 ← Mins (𝑋 ); insert 𝑛 𝑗 PLH tokens at gap 𝑗 if gap is editable\n\nToken\n\nLabel\nResult\n\n[122]\n\nSHIFT−2\n[120]\n\n[53]\n\nKEEP\n[53]\n\n[83]\n\n[53]\n\nSHIFT+2\n[85]\n\nAPPEND84\n[53] [84]\n\nSHIFT−2 corrects D4→C4; SHIFT+2 fixes the cascading interval to\nE4; APPEND84 inserts a position token for the missing G4 (81+3 = 84,\nrelative to E4). Since APPEND attaches only one token per anchor, the\npattern token for G4 cannot be produced within the same round.\n\nStep 3: Post-processing and convergence. The Decode-Filter-\nReencode step (Appendix E) parses the beat into complete (position,\npattern) pairs; the trailing token [84] lacks a pattern token, does\nnot form a valid note, and is discarded during re-encoding, yield-\ning [120][53] [85][53]. Both pitch errors are therefore fixed\nwithin a single iteration, while the missing G4 is not restored: even\nif a later iteration proposes the same APPEND, post-processing re-\nmoves the incomplete insertion again and the no-progress check\nterminates inference. This reflects a structural limitation of sep-\narated encodings—restoring a deleted note requires two coordi-\nnated tokens, but validity filtering only admits complete pairs—and\nis consistent with note deletion being the hardest error type for\nSchemes A and B (Figure 3). Under bundled encoding the same re-\npair is a single edit: in Scheme C the missing G4 corresponds to one\ncomposite token (3 × 81 + 53 = 296), so APPEND296 completes the in-\nsertion within one iteration and passes post-processing unchanged.\nThis walkthrough demonstrates that SHIFT and APPEND cooperate\nwithin a single iteration, and that Decode-Filter-Reencode acts\nas a structural safety net: every intermediate sequence remains\nwell-formed and decodable, at the cost of discarding insertions left\nincomplete at the end of an iteration.\n\nG Synthetic Perturbation Details\nH IterEdit Inference Algorithm\n\nI Generative Baseline Details\n\nThe main text reports summary results for the two generative\nbaselines; here we provide full per-scheme and per-configuration\n\n6: Mark all new PLH positions as editable\n7:\n\n// Step 3: Fill placeholders\n𝑋𝑖 ← arg max Mtok (𝑋 )𝑖 for each PLH position 𝑖\nif no deletions, no insertions, and no fills then\n\n8:\n\n9:\n\n10:\n\nbreak\n\nend if\n11:\n12: end for\n13: return 𝑋\n\nbreakdowns that reveal encoding sensitivity patterns consistent\nwith those observed for edit-based methods.\n\nI.1 Autoregressive LLM Baseline\n\nTo quantify the gap between autoregressive generation and edit-\nbased paradigms, we evaluate four LLaMA-based strategies (∼162M\nparameters, trained from scratch on the same data), ordered by the\namount of positional guidance provided:\n• AR-Prompt: takes the first 2 bars of the source as prompt and\nautoregressively generates the rest; the generated melody is re-\nplaced with the source melody post hoc.\n\n• AR-Teacher: melody beats are fed via teacher-forcing with ex-\nplicit track markers; all accompaniment beats are regenerated.\n• AR-Detect: a two-stage pipeline that uses SeqTag’s error detec-\ntion head to identify perturbed beats (any accompaniment token\nwith 𝑃 (error) ≥ 0.5 flags the beat), then regenerates only those\nbeats via LLaMA with melody teacher-forcing. This provides the\nfairest AR comparison, as it uses the same localization signal\navailable to edit methods.\n\n• AR-Selective: same teacher-forcing as Teacher, but only the\naccompaniment beats at oracle-known changed_beat_indices\nare regenerated; unperturbed beats retain the source content.\nThis is the most favorable setting for AR.\n\nImplementation. For Scheme A, melody beats start with Track0 (183)\nand accompaniment with Track1 (184); Teacher/Selective explicitly\ninsert 184 before sampling accompaniment content. For bundled\nschemes (C/D), SPLIT_0 (7129) and SPLIT_1 (7130) serve as track\n\n\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nHaoyu Gu et al.\n\nmarkers. For Scheme B (no explicit marker), beats alternate by\nposition and terminate with END_MARKER (170). Prompt/Full post-\nprocessing parses the generated sequence into beat pairs and re-\nplaces melody beats with source melody.\nFairness note. Edit methods (SeqTag/TagFill/IterEdit) see the com-\nplete corrupted source and must autonomously identify which\npositions need modification. AR-Prompt and AR-Teacher do not\nknow which beats are perturbed and regenerate all accompaniment.\nAR-Selective additionally receives oracle changed_beat_indices—\ninformation unavailable to edit methods. Results for Selective there-\nfore represent an upper bound on AR performance under ideal\nlocalization, not a fair head-to-head comparison.\n\nTable 17: LLaMA baseline results (𝑛 = 200, perturbed-only).\nBest per task–strategy in bold. †Selective receives oracle\nchanged-beat positions.\n\nStrategy\n\nTask\n\nSch.\n\nbeat↑\n\nnf1↑ MPE↓\n\nFMD↓\n\nAR-Select.†\n\nAR-Detect\n\nAR-Teacher\n\nAR-Prompt\n\nCorr.\nEdit.\nCompl.\n\nCorr.\nEdit.\n\nCorr.\nEdit.\nCompl.\n\nCorr.\nEdit.\nCompl.\n\nA\nA\nA\n\nA\nA\n\nB\nA\nC\n\nD\nA\nA\n\n.477\n.499\n.397\n\n.394\n.278\n\n.062\n.101\n.117\n\n.093\n.095\n.152\n\n.637\n.603\n.512\n\n.650\n.478\n\n.238\n.211\n.221\n\n.242\n.211\n.221\n\n8.6\n9.6\n14.4\n\n9.1\n15.2\n\n20.0\n25.6\n22.6\n\n16.3\n25.8\n18.7\n\n1.17\n0.85\n0.39\n\n1.24\n1.73\n\n5.74\n7.07\n5.82\n\n11.2\n3.89\n1.54\n\nThe results reveal a clear localization hierarchy. Prompt and\nTeacher, which lack positional guidance, achieve at most 0.152 beat\nexact match. Detect, using SeqTag’s error detector for automated\nlocalization, jumps to 0.394 on correction and 0.278 on editing—\na substantial improvement but still below edit methods (SeqTag:\n0.726, IterEdit: 0.480). Selective, given oracle positions, reaches\n0.477–0.499 but still cannot match per-token precision on correction\n(0.477 vs. 0.726). Detect is inapplicable to completion, as the error\ndetector cannot identify missing content.\n\nThe gap between Detect and edit methods is particularly infor-\nmative: both use the same localization signal (SeqTag’s detector),\nbut edit methods apply targeted token-level operations while De-\ntect regenerates entire beats via AR sampling. This confirms that\nthe editing mechanism itself—not just localization—is the source of\nthe performance advantage. Selective consistently favors Scheme A,\nand its FMD values (0.39–1.17) are competitive with edit methods,\nsuggesting that AR generation can produce distributionally natural\noutput at the cost of requiring oracle positional guidance.\n\nI.2 Discrete Diffusion Baseline\n\nWe evaluate D3PM [1] discrete diffusion (∼34M parameters) with\nan SDEdit-style noise-then-denoise strategy at three noise ratios:\n𝑟 =0.3 (30 denoising steps), 𝑟 =0.5 (50 steps), and 𝑟 =0.7 (70 steps). All\nmodels are trained on the same data with all four encoding schemes\n(𝑛 = 200, perturbed-only).\n\nThree findings are notable. First, performance degrades sharply\nwith noise ratio: 𝑟 =0.3 is the only competitive setting; 𝑟 =0.5 halves\nbeat exact match, and 𝑟 =0.7 collapses to near-zero on separated\nencodings (FMD >200, fail rate >93%). This confirms that SDEdit\nrequires minimal noise injection for editing—heavy noise destroys\nthe structural information that denoising cannot recover. Second,\nencoding dependence is extreme and mirrors edit methods: bundled\nschemes (C/D) outperform separated schemes (A/B) by 4–8× on\ncorrection (r03: Scheme D 0.390 vs. A 0.089). Separated encoding\ndistributes each note across two tokens; the diffusion process must\nindependently recover both tokens in a consistent pair, a coordi-\nnation problem that bundled encoding avoids. This parallel to edit\nmethods’ encoding sensitivity provides independent evidence that\nencoding choice is a universal design lever, not method-specific.\nThird, completion exposes diffusion’s fundamental limitation: Dif-\nfusion r03 maintains non-trivial beat exact match on completion\n(0.080) but low nf1 (0.228), and at higher noise ratios (𝑟 =0.5) nf1\ncollapses to 0.002, indicating that the denoising process recovers\nrhythmic structure but struggles with pitch content. TagFill’s nf1\nof 0.557 on the same task confirms that explicit generation mecha-\nnisms are required for content synthesis.\n\nJ Cross-Encoding Pre-Training Analysis\n\nTable 3 (main paper) reports a recovery metric defined as (nf1 −\nnf1no-edit)/(1 − nf1no-edit), measuring the fraction of the no-edit\nerror gap closed by the method. Beat achieves ∼5× higher recovery\nthan alternative encodings. Here we trace this gap to its root cause:\nencoding structure determines pre-training quality, which cascades\ninto downstream editing performance.\n\nJ.1 MLM Pre-Training Convergence\n\nAll four Beat schemes converge to PPL = 1.29–1.83, with relative-\nseparated (Scheme B) achieving the lowest perplexity (1.29). Bun-\ndled schemes (C/D) start from much higher initial PPL due to their\n7,145-token vocabulary but undergo a sharp phase transition around\nepoch 12–18, ultimately converging within 0.2–0.5 of separated\nschemes. Among alternative encodings, REMI and Structured con-\nverge normally (PPL = 1.39, 1.57), while MIDI-Like plateaus at 8.18—\n5–6× higher—reflecting its flat event-stream structure where inter-\nleaved NoteOn/NoteOff tokens across all 128 pitches create long-\nrange dependencies that MLM cannot capture. CPWord’s apparent\nPPL of ∼500 reflects its compound vocabulary structure (joint pre-\ndiction over 5 factored sub-vocabularies) rather than a failure to\nlearn; its downstream EditF1 confirms meaningful learning.\n\nK Full Per-Scheme Results\n\nTables 20 and 21 present the complete per-scheme breakdown for\nall method–task combinations (perturbed-only, 𝑛 = 200). The main\ntext (Tables 3 and 4) reports only the best-scheme result per method;\nthese appendix tables reveal the full encoding sensitivity. IterEdit\nwas evaluated across all four schemes. SeqTag cannot perform\nsegment completion (no generation head).\n\nSeveral patterns emerge. Encoding sensitivity: Scheme B remains\nthe weakest for TagFill and IterEdit, but SeqTag now achieves its\nhighest correction score on Scheme B (0.726), surpassing all other\nschemes. TagFill and IterEdit still exhibit sharp B-column drops on\n\n\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n\nACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nTable 18: Diffusion baseline results across noise ratios and encoding schemes (𝑛 = 200, perturbed-only). Best scheme per\nratio–task in bold.\n\nError Correction\n\nAccomp. Editing\n\nSegment Completion\n\nRatio Sch. beat\n\nnf1\n\nFMD fail beat\n\nnf1\n\nFMD fail beat\n\nnf1\n\nFMD fail\n\n𝑟 =0.3\n\n𝑟 =0.5\n\n𝑟 =0.7\n\nA\nB\nC\nD\n\nA\nB\nC\nD\n\nA\nB\nC\nD\n\n.190\n.124\n.515\n\n14.1\n.093\n17.4\n.048\n2.03\n.340\n.390 .602 0.87 .04 .198\n\n.134\n.076\n.075\n.088\n.200 .372\n.411\n\n.78\n.87\n.07\n\n.013\n.005\n.294\n\n.010\n.029\n.010\n.018\n.153\n.186\n.188 .358 3.32 .29 .105 .230\n\n.081\n.070\n.095\n\n217\n171\n3.90\n\n.98\n.99\n.37\n\n.002\n.000\n.133\n\n.000\n.020\n.000\n.015\n.057\n.085\n.067 .191 10.2 .67 .063 .113\n\n.101\n.085\n.046\n\n453\n355\n7.92\n\n1.0\n.99\n.76\n\n18.20\n22.08\n2.75\n1.72\n\n221\n172\n5.91\n5.43\n\n454\n353\n10.9\n14.5\n\n.168\n.053\n.82\n.119\n.050\n.80\n.228\n.080\n.22\n.23 .080 .228\n\n14.9\n19.6\n52.7\n37.5\n\n.028\n.005\n.071\n\n222\n.98\n173\n.95\n.50\n4.79\n.43 .074 .002 4.84\n\n.000\n.000\n.002\n\n.013\n.003\n.060\n\n455\n1.0\n359", "numLines": 800, "startLine": 2000, "totalLines": 4133}}}
