tof the main paper); “vanilla” uses the original contiguous-masking\n2918\tconfiguration; “Enc-Dec” replaces the encoder-only architecture\n2919\twith an encoder-decoder cross-attention design.\n2920\t\n2921\tThree ablation findings are notable. First, adding track-aware\n2922\tattention bias degrades both editing (0.448 → 0.428, −4.5%) and\n2923\tcorrection (0.719 → 0.666, −7.4%), confirming that shared atten-\n2924\ttion already captures inter-track dependencies without explicit\n2925\tstructural bias. Second, the 4× gap between full and vanilla configu-\n2926\trations on editing beat (.480 vs. .114) demonstrates that multi-level\n2927\tperturbation training is essential for IterEdit to generalize beyond\n2928\tcontiguous masking to fine-grained editing. Third, replacing the\n2929\tencoder-only architecture with an encoder-decoder design (Enc-\n2930\tDec, 66.5M vs. 33.9M parameters) collapses performance (editing:\n2931\t.051, correction: .034) with catastrophic FMD (>18), confirming that\n2932\tthe encoder-only inductive bias—where edited and context tokens\n2933\tshare attention—is critical for the editing paradigm.\n2934\t\n2935\tcorrection (0.061, 0.070) and editing (0.089, 0.069), suggesting that\n2936\tmulti-pass and generative methods are more sensitive to relative-\n2937\tseparated encoding than the single-pass classification approach of\n2938\tSeqTag. The optimal encoding is method-dependent: SeqTag favors\n2939\tScheme B for correction (0.726) and Scheme C for editing (0.408),\n2940\tTagFill favors Scheme A for correction (.368) and completion (.436)\n2941\tbut Scheme D for editing (.350), and IterEdit is task-dependent (A\n2942\tfor correction, D for editing). IterEdit encoding sensitivity: IterEdit’s\n2943\tcorrection on Scheme A (.719) far exceeds Scheme D (.569) and C\n2944\t(.412), a 0.307 gap—the largest encoding effect observed—yet for\n2945\tediting the pattern reverses (D: .480 > A: .458).\n2946\t\n2947\tL Ablation Studies\n2948\tL.1 IterEdit Architecture and Training Ablation\n2949\t\n2950\tTable 22 compares IterEdit training configurations and architectural\n2951\tablations on editing and correction (perturbed-only, 𝑛 = 200). The\n2952\t\n2953\tL.2 Pre-training Ablation\n2954\t\n2955\tTable 23 isolates the contribution of BERT pre-training by compar-\n2956\ting three SeqTag configurations on Scheme D (𝑛 = 200, perturbed-\n2957\tonly): the full pipeline (BERT pre-trained + fine-tuned), S1-only\n2958\t(BERT pre-trained, no task-specific S3 fine-tuning), and Scratch\n2959\t(randomly initialized, no pre-training).\n2960\t\n2961\tTwo findings emerge. First, removing BERT pre-training causes\n2962\tcatastrophic degradation: Scratch achieves only 0.195 correction\n2963\tbeat (−72% vs. Full) and 0.157 editing beat (−60%), confirming that\n2964\tdomain-specific pre-training—not the SeqTag architecture itself—is\n2965\tthe primary driver of performance. Second, the S1-only variant\n2966\tslightly exceeds the full pipeline (correction: 0.719 vs. 0.700; editing:\n2967\t0.401 vs. 0.390), suggesting that task-specific fine-tuning provides\n2968\tmarginal benefit when the pre-trained representations are already\n2969\twell-suited to the editing task. Combined with the IterEdit encoder-\n2970\tdecoder collapse above, these results identify two critical design\n2971\t\n2972\t\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n2973\t\n2974\tHaoyu Gu et al.\n2975\t\n2976\tTable 20: Beat exact match across all encoding schemes, methods, and tasks (𝑛 = 200). Best scheme per method–task cell in bold;\n2977\t“—” = not evaluated or not applicable.\n2978\t\n2979\tError Correction\n2980\t\n2981\tAccomp. Editing\n2982\t\n2983\tSegment Completion\n2984\t\n2985\t.030\n2986\t.129\n2987\t.222\n2988\t.726\n2989\t.070\n2990\t.061\n2991\t\n2992\tMethod\n2993\t\n2994\tA\n2995\t\n2996\tB\n2997\t\n2998\t.030\n2999\tNo-Edit\n3000\tCopy-Ctx\n3001\t.123\n3002\tBERT-CMLM .240\n3003\t\n3004\tB\n3005\t\n3006\tC\n3007\t\n3008\tC\n3009\t\n3