n3351\t—\n3352\t0.39\n3353\t5.69\n3354\t\n3355\t1.04\n3356\t3.80\n3357\t3.88\n3358\t\n3359\t—\n3360\t1.04\n3361\t0.52\n3362\t\n3363\t19.6\n3364\t7.17\n3365\t—\n3366\t1.20\n3367\t—\n3368\t\n3369\t1.76\n3370\t3.13\n3371\t2.53\n3372\t\n3373\t—\n3374\t2.49\n3375\t0.42\n3376\t\n3377\t52.7\n3378\t6.65\n3379\t—\n3380\t0.70\n3381\t—\n3382\t\n3383\tD\n3384\t\n3385\t1.95\n3386\t2.81\n3387\t2.35\n3388\t\n3389\t—\n3390\t2.39\n3391\t0.34\n3392\t\n3393\t37.5\n3394\t8.23\n3395\t—\n3396\t1.03\n3397\t—\n3398\t\n3399\tTable 22: IterEdit variant comparison (beat exact match /\n3400\tFMD, 𝑛 = 200). Values may differ slightly from the full per-\n3401\tscheme results due to different perturbation configurations\n3402\tused in ablation runs.\n3403\t\n3404\tVariant\n3405\t\n3406\tSch.\n3407\t\n3408\tEditing\n3409\t\n3410\tCorrection\n3411\t\n3412\tFull (multi-level perturb.) D\n3413\tFull (multi-level perturb.) A\n3414\tFull + track-aware bias\n3415\tA\n3416\tFull (multi-level perturb.) C\n3417\t\n3418\tvanilla (thr. = 0.3)\n3419\tvanilla (edit mode)\n3420\tEnc-Dec (cross-attn)\n3421\t\n3422\tD\n3423\tD\n3424\tD\n3425\t\n3426\t.480 / 1.19\n3427\t.448 / 2.52\n3428\t.428 / 2.54\n3429\t.341 / 2.61\n3430\t\n3431\t.114 / 2.71\n3432\t—\n3433\t.051 / 18.5\n3434\t\n3435\t.568 / 1.40\n3436\t.719 / 1.03\n3437\t.666 / 1.10\n3438\t.412 / 4.09\n3439\t\n3440\t—\n3441\t.129 / 2.27\n3442\t.034 / 24.3\n3443\t\n3444\tTable 23: SeqTag pre-training ablation (Scheme D, 𝑛 = 200,\n3445\tperturbed-only). Bold: best per task.\n3446\t\n3447\tVariant\n3448\t\n3449\tTask beat↑ nf1↑\n3450\t\n3451\tFMD↓\n3452\t\n3453\tFull (BERT + fine-tune) Corr.\n3454\tCorr.\n3455\tS1-only (BERT, no S3)\n3456\tCorr.\n3457\tScratch (random init)\n3458\t\n3459\tFull (BERT + fine-tune)\n3460\tS1-only (BERT, no S3)\n3461\tScratch (random init)\n3462\t\n3463\tEdit.\n3464\tEdit.\n3465\tEdit.\n3466\t\n3467\t.700\n3468\t.719\n3469\t.195\n3470\t\n3471\t.390\n3472\t.401\n3473\t.157\n3474\t\n3475\t.852\n3476\t.861\n3477\t.660\n3478\t\n3479\t.537\n3480\t.540\n3481\t.451\n3482\t\n3483\t0.09\n3484\t0.07\n3485\t1.45\n3486\t\n3487\t2.34\n3488\t2.27\n3489\t—\n3490\t\n3491\tchoices: (1) domain-specific BERT pre-training, and (2) encoder-\n3492\tonly architecture with shared attention over edited and context\n3493\ttokens.\n3494\t\n3495\t\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n3496\t\n3497\tACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n3498\t\n3499\tL.3 Per-Error-Type Analysis\n3500\t\n3501\tFigure 3 breaks down SeqTag correction performance by perturba-\n3502\ttion type across encoding schemes. Note insertion is easiest (Edit\n3503\tF1 > 0.87 for all schemes), as inserted notes create distinctive to-\n3504\tken patterns that the tagger readily detects. Rhythm changes are\n3505\talso well-handled (0.80–0.86). Pitch shifts are harder (0.32–0.67),\n3506\tespecially for bundled Scheme C where a single-token pitch change\n3507\trequires selecting from the full 7K vocabulary. Note deletion is the\n3508\tmost challenging (0.14–0.39), as the tagger must identify missing\n3509\tcontent from context alone.\n3510\t\n3511\tFigure 3: SeqTag correction Edit F1 by error type across en-\n3512\tcoding schemes (𝑛 = 30 per type).\n3513\t\n3514\tL.4 Sequence Length Effect\n3515\t\n3516\tFigure 4 shows how sequence length affects correction performance.\n3517\tShort sequences (<500 tokens) are harder for separated encod-\n3518\tings (A, B), likely due to limited context. Performance stabilizes\n3519\tfor medium and long sequences across all schemes, with bundled\n3520\tScheme C maintaining the highest Edit F1 throughout.\n3521\t\n3522\tFigure 4: SeqTag correction Edit F1 by sequence length across\n3523\tencoding schemes (𝑛 = 50 per bin).\n3524\t\n3525\tM Statistical Significance Tests\n3526\tAll significance tests use paired bootstrap resampling (𝐵 = 10,000)\n3527\tand Wilcoxon signed-rank tests on beat exact match (𝑛 = 200,\n3528\tperturbed-only). Effect sizes are reported as Cohen’s 𝑑 (S: small, M:\n3529\tmedium, L: large).\n3530\t\n3531\tM.1 Pairwise Method Comparisons\n3532\t\n3533\tThe key finding is that IterEdit and SeqTag are statistically equiv-\n3534\talent on correction at their respective best schemes (𝑝 = 0.489),\n3535\twhile IterEdit is significantly better on editing across all evaluated\n3536\tschemes (𝑝 < 0.001). All other pairwise comparisons are also highly\n3537\tsignificant (𝑝 < 0.001).\n3538\t\n3539\tM.2 Encoding × Method Interaction (ANOVA)\n3540\tAll encoding×method interactions are highly significant (𝑝 < 0.001),\n3541\tformally confirming that method rankings reverse across encod-\n3542\ting schemes. The interaction effect is largest for correction (𝜂2 =\n3543\t12.5%), driven primarily by TagFill and IterEdit’s sharp drops on\n3544\tScheme B (0.061, 0.070) while SeqTag achieves its highest score on\n3545\tB (0.726). For editing, the interaction (𝜂2 = 5.1%) reflects TagFill’s\n3546\tScheme B collapse (0.084) versus its competitive performance on\n3547\tother schemes. Encoding explains substantially more variance in\n3548\tcorrection (15.4%) than in editing (5.0%), consistent with the main\n3549\ttext finding that encoding is a stronger design lever for precision-\n3550\tdemanding tasks.\n3551\t\n3552\tN Subjective Evaluation Details\n3553\t\n3554\tWe recruited 33 evaluators from university students (34% no music\n3555\ttraining, 42% hobby-level, 18% formally trained 3+ years, 6% music\n3556\tmajors; 55% play an instrument; 52% listen daily). Systems were\n3557\tpresented in randomized blind order via a web interface with piano\n3558\troll visualizations and audio playback. Each evaluator provided 228\n3559\tratings across four experiments on three dimensions: music quality\n3560\t(MQ), naturalness (NA), and edit accuracy (EA), using a 1–5 MOS\n3561\tscale. Tables 26–29 report per-dimension scores.\n3562\t\n3563\tO Efficiency Analysis\n3564\t\n3565\tTable 30 reports per-task latency for all methods. Single-pass meth-\n3566\tods (CMLM, SeqTag, TagFill) are stable across tasks (37–65 ms).\n3567\tIterEdit varies substantially: completion requires few iterations\n3568\t(82 ms) while editing requires many (655 ms). AR latency depends\n3569\ton the generation strategy and output length.\n3570\t\n3571\tArchitecture-agnostic FLOPs. Wall-clock latency is affected by\n3572\timplementation and model size. For an implementation-independent\n3573\tview, Table 31 reports analytically estimated single-sample infer-\n3574\tence FLOPs (standard transformer accounting, equal sequence\n3575\tlength 2,048). Editing methods complete inference in 1–3 forward\n3576\tpasses (172–517 GFLOPs). Notably, AR totals only 789 GFLOPs\n3577\tthanks to KV caching, yet is two orders of magnitude slower in wall-\n3578\tclock time because its 2,048 decoding steps must execute strictly\n3579\tsequentially; D3PM requires 30 denoising passes (5,604 GFLOPs).\n3580\tThe efficiency advantage of editing is thus paradigmatic—few par-\n3581\tallel passes—rather than an artifact of implementation-level opti-\n3582\tmization.\n3583\t\n3584\tWe further examine how encoding scheme affects inference\n3585\t\n3586\tspeed within the SeqTag pipeline.\n3587\t\n3588\t\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n3589\t\n3590\tHaoyu Gu et al.\n3591\t\n3592\tTable 24: Key pairwise comparisons (beat exact match, 10,000 bootstrap resamples). Significance at 𝛼 = 0.05.\n3593\t\n3594\tComparison (A vs. B) Task\n3595\t\n3596\tSch. Mean A Mean B\n3597\t\n3598\t𝚫\n3599\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "a6c26182-3b6c-4097-bc3f-bca74a622107", "uuid": "275c98da-1c21-4869-b668-ae274298e9da", "timestamp": "2026-07-14T08:07:05.127Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/beatedit_full.txt", "content": ".93\n.79\n10.2\n.71 .061 .003 11.1\n\n.000\n.000\n.002\n\n.99\n.97\n.65\n.65\n\n.99\n1.0\n.68\n.70\n\n1.0\n1.0\n.79\n.78\n\nTable 19: MLM pre-training convergence across encodings.\nValues are eval perplexity (↓). PPL values are not directly\ncomparable across encodings with different vocabulary struc-\ntures (see text).\n\nEncoding\n\nVocab\n\nEp. 6\n\nEp. 12\n\nEp. 18\n\nEp. 24\n\nEp. 30\n\nBeat (Abs, Sep)\nBeat (Rel, Sep)\nBeat (Rel, Bun)\nBeat (Abs, Bun)\n\n186\n185\n7,145\n7,145\n\n14.98\n8.77\n60.08\n86.35\n\n1.70\n1.47\n2.47\n20.81\n\n1.46\n1.33\n1.77\n2.29\n\n1.40\n1.30\n1.66\n1.88\n\n1.39\n1.29\n1.63\n1.83\n\n284\n317\n306∗\n403\n\n16.49\n3.61\n544\n20.54\n\nREMI\n2.70\nStructured\n2.21\nCPWord‡\n509\nMIDI-Like†\n11.43\n∗CPWord uses 5 compound sub-vocabs (6×38×156×37×69); PPL reflects joint prediction\nspace and is not comparable to flat-vocabulary encodings.\n†BERT MLM converged to substantially higher PPL (8.18 vs. ∼1.5).\n‡CPWord PPL reflects compound vocabulary (see text).\n\n1.51\n1.74\n504\n9.06\n\n1.40\n1.60\n500\n8.43\n\n1.39\n1.57\n501\n8.18\n\n“full” variants use the multi-level perturbation strategy (Section 3.3\nof the main paper); “vanilla” uses the original contiguous-masking\nconfiguration; “Enc-Dec” replaces the encoder-only architecture\nwith an encoder-decoder cross-attention design.\n\nThree ablation findings are notable. First, adding track-aware\nattention bias degrades both editing (0.448 → 0.428, −4.5%) and\ncorrection (0.719 → 0.666, −7.4%), confirming that shared atten-\ntion already captures inter-track dependencies without explicit\nstructural bias. Second, the 4× gap between full and vanilla configu-\nrations on editing beat (.480 vs. .114) demonstrates that multi-level\nperturbation training is essential for IterEdit to generalize beyond\ncontiguous masking to fine-grained editing. Third, replacing the\nencoder-only architecture with an encoder-decoder design (Enc-\nDec, 66.5M vs. 33.9M parameters) collapses performance (editing:\n.051, correction: .034) with catastrophic FMD (>18), confirming that\nthe encoder-only inductive bias—where edited and context tokens\nshare attention—is critical for the editing paradigm.\n\ncorrection (0.061, 0.070) and editing (0.089, 0.069), suggesting that\nmulti-pass and generative methods are more sensitive to relative-\nseparated encoding than the single-pass classification approach of\nSeqTag. The optimal encoding is method-dependent: SeqTag favors\nScheme B for correction (0.726) and Scheme C for editing (0.408),\nTagFill favors Scheme A for correction (.368) and completion (.436)\nbut Scheme D for editing (.350), and IterEdit is task-dependent (A\nfor correction, D for editing). IterEdit encoding sensitivity: IterEdit’s\ncorrection on Scheme A (.719) far exceeds Scheme D (.569) and C\n(.412), a 0.307 gap—the largest encoding effect observed—yet for\nediting the pattern reverses (D: .480 > A: .458).\n\nL Ablation Studies\nL.1 IterEdit Architecture and Training Ablation\n\nTable 22 compares IterEdit training configurations and architectural\nablations on editing and correction (perturbed-only, 𝑛 = 200). The\n\nL.2 Pre-training Ablation\n\nTable 23 isolates the contribution of BERT pre-training by compar-\ning three SeqTag configurations on Scheme D (𝑛 = 200, perturbed-\nonly): the full pipeline (BERT pre-trained + fine-tuned), S1-only\n(BERT pre-trained, no task-specific S3 fine-tuning), and Scratch\n(randomly initialized, no pre-training).\n\nTwo findings emerge. First, removing BERT pre-training causes\ncatastrophic degradation: Scratch achieves only 0.195 correction\nbeat (−72% vs. Full) and 0.157 editing beat (−60%), confirming that\ndomain-specific pre-training—not the SeqTag architecture itself—is\nthe primary driver of performance. Second, the S1-only variant\nslightly exceeds the full pipeline (correction: 0.719 vs. 0.700; editing:\n0.401 vs. 0.390), suggesting that task-specific fine-tuning provides\nmarginal benefit when the pre-trained representations are already\nwell-suited to the editing task. Combined with the IterEdit encoder-\ndecoder collapse above, these results identify two critical design\n\n\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nHaoyu Gu et al.\n\nTable 20: Beat exact match across all encoding schemes, methods, and tasks (𝑛 = 200). Best scheme per method–task cell in bold;\n“—” = not evaluated or not applicable.\n\nError Correction\n\nAccomp. Editing\n\nSegment Completion\n\n.030\n.129\n.222\n.726\n.070\n.061\n\nMethod\n\nA\n\nB\n\n.030\nNo-Edit\nCopy-Ctx\n.123\nBERT-CMLM .240\n\nB\n\nC\n\nC\n\n.030\n.097\n.327\n\nD\n\n.030\n.097\n.388\n\nA\n\n.037\n.127\n.134\n\n.037\n.127\n.146\n\nD\n\n.037\n.094\n.188\n\nA\n\n.000\n.116\n.111\n\n.394\n.069\n.089\n\n.702\n.412\n.335\n\n.382\n.458\n.321\n\n.700\n.719\n.368\n\nSeqTag\nIterEdit\nTagFill\n\n.700\n.569\n.329\n.390\nDiffusion\n.093\nAR-Prompt\n.264\nAR-Detect\nAR-Select.†\n.171\nAnticipatory‡\n—\n‡Anticipatory operates on raw MIDI; Scheme A results shown for reference (encoding-independent).\n\n.076\n.095\n.278\n.499\n—\n\n.093\n.091\n.394\n.477\n—\n\n.053\n.152\n—\n.397\n.069\n\n.198\n.084\n.212\n.203\n—\n\n.075\n.087\n.172\n.262\n—\n\n.340\n.091\n.306\n.216\n—\n\n.048\n.069\n.194\n.216\n—\n\n.399\n.480\n.350\n\n—\n.120\n.436\n\n.037\n.094\n.186\n.408\n.352\n.301\n.200\n.089\n.239\n.236\n—\n\nB\n\nC\n\n.000\n.067\n.050\n\n—\n.060\n.264\n\n.050\n.105\n—\n.068\n—\n\n.000\n.002\n.000\n\n—\n.011\n.298\n\n.080\n.044\n—\n.240\n—\n\nD\n\n.000\n.002\n.000\n\n—\n.005\n.326\n\n.080\n.043\n—\n.146\n—\n\nTable 21: Fréchet Music Distance (FMD, ↓) across all encoding schemes, methods, and tasks (𝑛 = 200). Best scheme per method–\ntask cell in bold.\n\nError Correction\n\nAccomp. Editing\n\nSegment Completion\n\nMethod\n\nA\n\nB\n\nC\n\nD\n\nA\n\n2.89\nNo-Edit\nCopy-Ctx\n4.14\nBERT-CMLM 0.88\n0.08\n1.03\n2.03\n\nSeqTag\nIterEdit\nTagFill\n\nDiffusion\nAR-Prompt\nAR-Detect\nAR-Select.†\nAnticipatory‡\n\n14.1\n5.56\n1.24\n1.17\n—\n\n5.33\n7.74\n2.05\n\n0.15\n8.20\n3.81\n\n17.4\n11.8\n3.97\n3.79\n—\n\n6.79\n9.28\n2.86\n\n0.32\n4.09\n4.02\n\n2.03\n14.2\n3.34\n4.93\n—\n\n2.69\n3.90\n1.01\n\n0.09\n1.40\n1.78\n\n0.87\n11.2\n1.62\n2.36\n—\n\n2.83\n3.80\n1.22\n\n1.86\n1.52\n0.99\n\n18.20\n3.89\n1.73\n0.11\n—\n\nB\n\n3.74\n5.48\n1.50\n\n1.87\n3.52\n2.53\n\n22.08\n6.42\n3.13\n1.93\n—\n\nC\n\n4.50\n6.97\n1.32\n\n2.56\n2.00\n0.83\n2.75\n7.14\n2.33\n1.79\n—\n\nD\n2.48\n3.62\n0.97\n\n1.58\n1.19\n1.24\n\n1.72\n6.90\n1.56\n1.18\n—\n\nA\n\nB\n\nC\n\n3.05\n2.62\n2.22\n\n—\n0.34\n0.27\n\n14.9\n1.54\n—\n0.39\n5.69\n\n1.04\n3.80\n3.88\n\n—\n1.04\n0.52\n\n19.6\n7.17\n—\n1.20\n—\n\n1.76\n3.13\n2.53\n\n—\n2.49\n0.42\n\n52.7\n6.65\n—\n0.70\n—\n\nD\n\n1.95\n2.81\n2.35\n\n—\n2.39\n0.34\n\n37.5\n8.23\n—\n1.03\n—\n\nTable 22: IterEdit variant comparison (beat exact match /\nFMD, 𝑛 = 200). Values may differ slightly from the full per-\nscheme results due to different perturbation configurations\nused in ablation runs.\n\nVariant\n\nSch.\n\nEditing\n\nCorrection\n\nFull (multi-level perturb.) D\nFull (multi-level perturb.) A\nFull + track-aware bias\nA\nFull (multi-level perturb.) C\n\nvanilla (thr. = 0.3)\nvanilla (edit mode)\nEnc-Dec (cross-attn)\n\nD\nD\nD\n\n.480 / 1.19\n.448 / 2.52\n.428 / 2.54\n.341 / 2.61\n\n.114 / 2.71\n—\n.051 / 18.5\n\n.568 / 1.40\n.719 / 1.03\n.666 / 1.10\n.412 / 4.09\n\n—\n.129 / 2.27\n.034 / 24.3\n\nTable 23: SeqTag pre-training ablation (Scheme D, 𝑛 = 200,\nperturbed-only). Bold: best per task.\n\nVariant\n\nTask beat↑ nf1↑\n\nFMD↓\n\nFull (BERT + fine-tune) Corr.\nCorr.\nS1-only (BERT, no S3)\nCorr.\nScratch (random init)\n\nFull (BERT + fine-tune)\nS1-only (BERT, no S3)\nScratch (random init)\n\nEdit.\nEdit.\nEdit.\n\n.700\n.719\n.195\n\n.390\n.401\n.157\n\n.852\n.861\n.660\n\n.537\n.540\n.451\n\n0.09\n0.07\n1.45\n\n2.34\n2.27\n—\n\nchoices: (1) domain-specific BERT pre-training, and (2) encoder-\nonly architecture with shared attention over edited and context\ntokens.\n\n\fBeatEdit: Symbolic Music Generation as Explicit Editing\n\nACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nL.3 Per-Error-Type Analysis\n\nFigure 3 breaks down SeqTag correction performance by perturba-\ntion type across encoding schemes. Note insertion is easiest (Edit\nF1 > 0.87 for all schemes), as inserted notes create distinctive to-\nken patterns that the tagger readily detects. Rhythm changes are\nalso well-handled (0.80–0.86). Pitch shifts are harder (0.32–0.67),\nespecially for bundled Scheme C where a single-token pitch change\nrequires selecting from the full 7K vocabulary. Note deletion is the\nmost challenging (0.14–0.39), as the tagger must identify missing\ncontent from context alone.\n\nFigure 3: SeqTag correction Edit F1 by error type across en-\ncoding schemes (𝑛 = 30 per type).\n\nL.4 Sequence Length Effect\n\nFigure 4 shows how sequence length affects correction performance.\nShort sequences (<500 tokens) are harder for separated encod-\nings (A, B), likely due to limited context. Performance stabilizes\nfor medium and long sequences across all schemes, with bundled\nScheme C maintaining the highest Edit F1 throughout.\n\nFigure 4: SeqTag correction Edit F1 by sequence length across\nencoding schemes (𝑛 = 50 per bin).\n\nM Statistical Significance Tests\nAll significance tests use paired bootstrap resampling (𝐵 = 10,000)\nand Wilcoxon signed-rank tests on beat exact match (𝑛 = 200,\nperturbed-only). Effect sizes are reported as Cohen’s 𝑑 (S: small, M:\nmedium, L: large).\n\nM.1 Pairwise Method Comparisons\n\nThe key finding is that IterEdit and SeqTag are statistically equiv-\nalent on correction at their respective best schemes (𝑝 = 0.489),\nwhile IterEdit is significantly better on editing across all evaluated\nschemes (𝑝 < 0.001). All other pairwise comparisons are also highly\nsignificant (𝑝 < 0.001).\n\nM.2 Encoding × Method Interaction (ANOVA)\nAll encoding×method interactions are highly significant (𝑝 < 0.001),\nformally confirming that method rankings reverse across encod-\ning schemes. The interaction effect is largest for correction (𝜂2 =\n12.5%), driven primarily by TagFill and IterEdit’s sharp drops on\nScheme B (0.061, 0.070) while SeqTag achieves its highest score on\nB (0.726). For editing, the interaction (𝜂2 = 5.1%) reflects TagFill’s\nScheme B collapse (0.084) versus its competitive performance on\nother schemes. Encoding explains substantially more variance in\ncorrection (15.4%) than in editing (5.0%), consistent with the main\ntext finding that encoding is a stronger design lever for precision-\ndemanding tasks.\n\nN Subjective Evaluation Details\n\nWe recruited 33 evaluators from university students (34% no music\ntraining, 42% hobby-level, 18% formally trained 3+ years, 6% music\nmajors; 55% play an instrument; 52% listen daily). Systems were\npresented in randomized blind order via a web interface with piano\nroll visualizations and audio playback. Each evaluator provided 228\nratings across four experiments on three dimensions: music quality\n(MQ), naturalness (NA), and edit accuracy (EA), using a 1–5 MOS\nscale. Tables 26–29 report per-dimension scores.\n\nO Efficiency Analysis\n\nTable 30 reports per-task latency for all methods. Single-pass meth-\nods (CMLM, SeqTag, TagFill) are stable across tasks (37–65 ms).\nIterEdit varies substantially: completion requires few iterations\n(82 ms) while editing requires many (655 ms). AR latency depends\non the generation strategy and output length.\n\nArchitecture-agnostic FLOPs. Wall-clock latency is affected by\nimplementation and model size. For an implementation-independent\nview, Table 31 reports analytically estimated single-sample infer-\nence FLOPs (standard transformer accounting, equal sequence\nlength 2,048). Editing methods complete inference in 1–3 forward\npasses (172–517 GFLOPs). Notably, AR totals only 789 GFLOPs\nthanks to KV caching, yet is two orders of magnitude slower in wall-\nclock time because its 2,048 decoding steps must execute strictly\nsequentially; D3PM requires 30 denoising passes (5,604 GFLOPs).\nThe efficiency advantage of editing is thus paradigmatic—few par-\nallel passes—rather than an artifact of implementation-level opti-\nmization.\n\nWe further examine how encoding scheme affects inference\n\nspeed within the SeqTag pipeline.\n\n\fACM MM ’26, November 10–14, 2026, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n\nHaoyu Gu et al.\n\nTable 24: Key pairwise comparisons (beat exact match, 10,000 bootstrap resamples). Significance at 𝛼 = 0.05.\n\nComparison (A vs. B) Task\n\nSch. Mean A Mean B\n\n𝚫\n", "numLines": 800, "startLine": 2800, "totalLines": 4133}}}
